WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:11.000
Are you ready?

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:12.000
I'm ready.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:19.000
I'm Emily Crosby with the Southern oral history program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:23.000
And I'm conducting this oral history as part of the Civil Rights History Project,

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:29.000
an undertaking of the Smithsonian Institution's National Museum of African American History and Culture,

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:32.000
and the American Folklife Center in the Library of Congress.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:43.000
Today is May 28th, and we are here at Mrs. Linda Fuller Degelmann and at her home in Americus, Georgia.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:49.000
And I'm here also with John Bishop, and we're really pleased to be with you today.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:53.000
Thank you, Emilye. It's a pleasure to be here with you and John.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:59.000
I was wondering if you could start by telling us a little bit about your family and background growing up in Alabama.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:00.000
Is that?

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:02.000
Yes.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:07.000
I was born in Birmingham, Alabama in 1941.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:20.000
And that happened to be the phenomenal year when the atom bomb was used in Japan.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:25.000
So of course I was unaware of that at that time.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:33.000
But my father is a businessman, graduate of the University of Alabama.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:38.000
I thought that it would be good for him to become active in the Army.

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:48.000
I think actually that was the days when reserve units were called into active duty.

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:57.000
And he didn't go overseas, but he was assigned to the procurement office for the Army in Philadelphia.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:05.000
So when I was still a toddler, we moved to Philadelphia for a couple of years.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:14.000
When the war was over, we moved back to Alabama and settled in Tuscaloosa, Alabama.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:24.000
And that's where I was raised until I married in 1959.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:28.000
Did your father continue to work at the end of the business?

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:40.000
He did. After the war, he and my mother started business in downtown Tuscaloosa called Caldwell Electric Company.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:43.000
It was right on Broad Street.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:48.000
And so I became very familiar with all kinds of appliances.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:56.000
I think we were the first ones in town, in the city, to have a dishwasher.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:08.000
And maybe one of the first televisions, you know, with the big antennas on top of our house.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:14.000
And so they were very engaged in business while I was growing up in school.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:18.000
I have one older sister.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:32.000
And one thing that I was real sharp in my memory about my dad's business related to the Southern culture at that time was he had repair,

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:35.000
a repair shop down in the basement of a store.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:40.000
And one of the guys was a black man.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:46.000
And I think he was mostly involved in delivering appliances that were sold.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:55.000
My dad would have, my dad and mom would have an annual picnic cookout at their house every year.

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:59.000
And he never would be invited.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:03.000
And I remember wondering about that.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:06.000
You know, why was not he included?

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:09.000
And of course, I went to segregated schools.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:15.000
And there was just no question about whether they should be integrated.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:19.000
You know, the way things were.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:28.000
Being a university town, I think the University of Alabama, I think we were exposed to more integrations.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:31.000
Integrated situations.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:40.000
Although it was after I married that the university was actually integrated.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:46.000
You said you remember wondering why does one employee wasn't ever invited or wasn't at the picnic?

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:52.000
Did you ever ask your parents or do you know why you thought about that?

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:58.000
I think I did bring it up, but it was just sort of dismissed.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:02.000
I don't remember a specific answer.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:05.000
Do you remember, I mean, other than that, which is really interesting.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:15.000
Do you remember sort of when you first began to think about race and sort of understand the separation and the hierarchies' physics system?

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:20.000
Well, actually, I think it was after I married.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:24.000
Like I said, I married in 1959.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:32.000
And my husband, Millard (Dean) Fuller, had been very active in youth work in his church.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:40.000
And often there would be like a conference, youth conference, up in the north somewhere.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:46.000
And when he would go up there, he became aware of some differences.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:52.000
Specifically, he remembered being greeted by a black woman.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:57.000
And he thought, wow, that was pretty interesting.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:00.000
So he was at the conference with black people.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:08.000
And he had a different perspective outside of his upbringing,

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:15.000
which was on the Georgia Alabama border around West Point, Georgia.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:26.000
So he became aware of some transitions that were taking place.

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:31.000
And so I picked up an awareness from him.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:37.000
We talked about how things were segregated.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:44.000
And we tried to reach out to black people whenever we had an opportunity to.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:51.000
And I began to realize, hey, they are just people like me.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:56.000
But it was mostly in a church setting.

00:06:56.000 --> 00:06:59.000
So you got a couple of questions about that.

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:03.000
Do you remember things like the Brown decision or the Montgomery bus boycott?

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:08.000
I guess you would have been in a school or maybe even a little younger for those?

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:13.000
You know, right after Millard (Dean) Fuller and I married, we moved to Montgomery.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:21.000
And he and a fellow law student had gone in business while they were in law school.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:26.000
And they set up a law practice in Montgomery.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:34.000
I attended Huntingdon College, which was, I think, all white at that time.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:43.000
But then things were occurring like the bus boycott.

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:47.000
Because while I was in school, I also had children.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:52.000
And I needed someone to come to the house to keep the children.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:58.000
And so I always had to go into town to pick up the lady.

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:03.000
Of course, as the buses, she wouldn't ride the bus.

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:06.000
And it was an inconvenience.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:13.000
But yet, here again, I just accepted it as the way things were.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:17.000
Yeah. And then there was the Selma to Montgomery March.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:20.000
Actually, let me back up.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:25.000
The next conflict in Montgomery were the Freedom Rides.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:32.000
And Millard (Dean) Fuller and Morris Dees actually went down to the bus station out of curiosity.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:37.000
Just to see what would happen when some of those buses came in.

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:47.000
And they were shocked at how people were beat up as soon as they stepped off the bus.

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:54.000
Well, yeah, there may have been several different Freedom Rides that came into Montgomery.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:09:01.000
But this particular one, I can remember how they were just shocked at how brutally people were beat up.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:08.000
And they began to think, hey, this is something wrong with this picture here.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:10.000
This is terrible.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:17.000
You know, both of them grew up in the church and they knew about brotherly love.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:21.000
And times were already beginning to change.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:28.000
The thoughts of equality and justice and that kind of thing.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:39.000
But what they witnessed just made them their minds shift 180 degrees.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:49.000
And whereas they had been sort of part of the Klan, they had been in politics in law school

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:55.000
and had spoken on behalf of the man running for Lieutenant Governor.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:10:03.000
And they went to Klan rallies to speak on behalf of MacDonald Gallion.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:07.000
They never were members of the Klan.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:20.000
But they were actually sort of members on the side because they received the issues of what was called the The Fiery Cross.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:23.000
That was a publication.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:25.000
I don't know how widespread it was.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:30.000
It may have been just Alabama Klan that published it.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:39.000
But they had represented a man that I forgot exactly what the case was.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:48.000
But they had represented a member of the Klan for some kind of legal action.

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:52.000
And they called him into their office.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:55.000
Apparently he was one of the leaders.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:11:07.000
And they told him that they wanted to cancel their prescription to the The Fiery Cross.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:14.000
And Morris (Dees) kind of took a pistol out and put it on his desk.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:17.000
And they said it.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:23.000
We want to cancel our subscription to the The Fiery Cross.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:30.000
And it was just a few nights later when their offices, Fuller & Dees Marketing,

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:39.000
was broken into and a lot of typewriters smashed, you know, paint slung on the wall,

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:45.000
and a lot of time, you know, I don't know how language sprayed on the wall.

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:59.000
And so they began to get repercussions and learn that this was not a very popular thing to do, but they knew it was right.

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:01.000
How did you feel about it?

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:06.000
As they're going through this change, you just have an impact on you?

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:14.000
I didn't see the beatings that occurred from the Freedom Rides, but of course I heard them talk about it.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:18.000
And I thought myself, this isn't right.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:26.000
And then there was the Selma to Montgomery March.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:35.000
Some pastors that Millard (Dean) Fuller knew up in Ohio, Indiana, I forgot now where they were from, came down to participate.

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:41.000
And they had a place to stay and they got in touch with Millard (Dean) Fuller and said, hey, you know, can we put our bed roll down?

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:46.000
And you live in one floor and have a place to sleep at night.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:49.000
And of course Millard (Dean) Fuller said, sure.

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:53.000
And our neighbors found out about it.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:59.000
We got some pretty nasty phone calls.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:15.000
And not only did the marchers, there were four or five, six of them would stay at our house, but Millard (Dean) Fuller and Morris would take them back to the march route each morning.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:25.000
And they can remember their license plate on the car, you know, a photograph of their license plate.

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:33.000
And thus we got some additional nasty calls, you know, from the broader community.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:42.000
So they made a stand.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:47.000
And it wasn't real significant.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:58.000
We never participated in any marches ourselves, but we definitely began to observe, begin to see, you know, that times were changing.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:01.000
They needed to change.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:06.000
And we just felt so badly for people who were discriminated against.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:12.000
And we decided, you know, we, somehow or another, we needed to get on the side.

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:20.000
And you set your sort of social life, your church life in Montgomery, while you're still living there in Lions Club, sort of, we thinking.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:24.000
Well, our neighbors wouldn't speak to us ever again.

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:31.000
We actually left Millard (Dean) Fuller not left Montgomery in 1965.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:36.000
This is a whole other story about our marriage crisis.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:41.000
Millard (Dean) Fuller and Morris both wanted to become millionaires by age 30.

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:45.000
And that was requiring them to work night and day, night and day.

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:50.000
And it basically just destroyed our marriage. I left Millard (Dean) Fuller.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:15:00.000
And out of that marriage crisis, we felt called to give away all of our wealth.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:04.000
And basically start totally over again.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:12.000
And we said, we want God to be in control this time. We've been doing what we want to do. We want God to be in control.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:15.000
So this was mid-60s.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:21.000
And Millard (Dean) Fuller had a lot of energy. He didn't want to just sit around, you know.

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:37.000
So the pastor that I counseled with at Broadway United Church of Christ, Dr. Durgan, was on the board of Tougaloo College.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:44.000
And so, predominantly, our totally black college then in Mississippi.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:53.000
And Millard (Dean) Fuller asked him, you know, what, do you have any ideas on what we could do?

00:15:53.000 --> 00:16:04.000
Now that I left business, sold my interest, half interest to my partner, Morris Dees," who by the way started Southern Poverty Law Center.

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:18.000
And that was five or six years later. He continued Fuller & Dees Marketing for a number of years before he started Southern Poverty Law Center.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:28.000
And so, Dr. Durgan said, well, I'm on the board for to glue. And we so badly need a new dorm.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:33.000
And he said, how would you like to raise the money for this new dorm on campus?

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:39.000
So, okay, you know, I know how to make money. I know how to raise money. So, we said, okay.

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:50.000
Well, actually it was because we kept a little bit of money to live on. I think they got a little bit of a salary.

00:16:50.000 --> 00:17:06.000
You know, we had three kids by that time. And we actually planted ourselves in the New York City area. Dr. Durgan provided an office for Millard (Dean) Fuller to work out of.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:13.000
Because, I mean, we couldn't come back to Montgomery to raise money. The money was in the North.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:28.000
And so, he needed that that that environment to raise that significant money. And we actually settled our family in New Jersey for two years.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:37.000
Almost have been a change for you. Well, it was. But I'm the type of person that I don't mind the challenge.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:50.000
And it was a whole new, exciting chapter in our lives. We had become so miserable with so much wealth and stuff.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:18:04.000
And the failing of our marriage, that we wanted to get back to basics. He and I both had a simple middle class upbringing.

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:19.000
And it felt good to get kind of back to the basics and be focused on something bigger than ourselves. Something with meaning, something that would put our Christian faith into action.

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:28.000
When you're living in New Jersey, what was the racial dynamics like there at that time in a community that you were part of?

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:42.000
Well, as best as I can remember in Montclair and the Glen Ridge area, it was predominantly white.

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:54.000
I think it was because of the economy. It was sort of a wealthy, bedroom suburb we lived in. We rented a bottom floor of a house.

00:18:54.000 --> 00:19:05.000
So we didn't live in one of those really nice houses in that area. But Millard commuted into the city by bus every day.

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:20.000
Our oldest child, son Chris, went to first grade there. And it seemed like there were two or three black children in the class.

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:35.000
There didn't seem to be any racial discrimination as far as housing was concerned. It was more affordability issue, I think, for most black families in that area.

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:52.000
Of course, Newark was close by, but that was another county. So the population of schools would probably have been integrated but predominantly black. There you see.

00:19:52.000 --> 00:20:03.000
But by that time, we had become very comfortable around black people, even sought out friendships with black families.

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:10.000
It was a different environment from being in the South for sure.

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:31.000
I was wondering if with the freedom rides, when you were talking about your husband and Laura Steeze going and looking at that, you know, and seeing that violence and the impact it had and their previous affiliation with the client.

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:51.000
I guess a couple of questions. Do you remember what, you know, were they sympathetic to the client? Or was this a practical kind of political affiliation? I mean, I know you said they weren't exactly members, but going and speaking. Do you remember how they felt about it before they began to question?

00:20:51.000 --> 00:21:10.000
Well, it was just like there's the Lions Club or the Kiwanis Club. You know, their activities were different. They weren't really a part of the meetings other than back in law school and the late 50s going to speak.

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:21.000
It was sort of a political alliance kind of thing. Well, yeah, they kind of accepted it. You know, I guess they thought they were a little radical, but.

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:35.000
But one of the pieces of background information I got mentioned something about that they're locked from defended some of the white men involved in the attacks on the freedom riders.

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:44.000
Do you know anything about that? You know that that. No, I don't.

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:50.000
I don't know. That was the person that they were having that interaction with around the fire across or.

00:21:50.000 --> 00:22:03.000
It could have been, but I'm not sure. I may have it in some notes somewhere. I wish Miller would hear because he could have told you every little detail about that.

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:15.000
I bet. Yes, definitely. What was Huntington like during that period was there. I think Bob Zellner, one of the student activists graduated from Huntington in the late 50s.

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:28.000
And he talks about maybe even earlier, but he talks about taking a sociology class and they ended up doing some firsthand research that involved going to meet Albany Movement jail and some of them got kicked out of school.

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:37.000
But in some ways it was also a good environment for him at least. So I wonder what it was like for you to be attending Huntington at that time.

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:46.000
I don't remember any kind of activity like that. I was married and living at home. So I wasn't real active on campus.

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:58.000
As if I had it would have been had I lived in the dorm. I was there beginning 1961 through 66.

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:04.000
And it could have happened either before or after.

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:13.000
You would have been there before you were there. But I just was curious whether any of your professors talked about race at all.

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:17.000
Or if that was just sort of outside of that.

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:42.000
No, it was. It was the Christian emphasis was still pretty strong at the college. Some colleges and universities that started off with a more firmer Christian association.

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:54.000
It was still. I remember old and New Testament required for every freshman entering ethics and philosophy were required.

00:23:54.000 --> 00:24:10.000
And that really broadened my mind a whole lot the ethics and philosophy because it examined values and every aspect of life.

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:20.000
So that you could kind of objectively look at yourself and your environment and decide what is valuable.

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:31.000
And well, I'm trying to think I don't remember any black students there.

00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:44.000
I don't know that they would have been excluded had they applied. It was pretty expensive. I only got to go there because Millard (Dean) Fuller was financing my education.

00:24:44.000 --> 00:25:00.000
He was able to do that. But here again as far as the housing is concerned it might have been. It was probably just not affordable or black students may not have felt comfortable.

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:17.000
But I know after I left in the 70s or 80s there was a real effort to recruit to bring more diverse student population to Huntington.

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:21.000
And of course I think that exists today.

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:28.000
Okay, we're back again.

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:34.000
Imagine you must have been pretty busy with the small children going to school.

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:52.000
Yes, my parents had really implanted in my and my sisters mine that we should strive to get our at least undergraduate degree.

00:25:52.000 --> 00:26:07.000
And in fact I married when I was 18 and I promised my parents that if I married at that young age that I would continue. I would go to school.

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:21.000
Well, we had our first baby 11 months after we married. So when he was 10 months old that's when we had moved among them and I enrolled in Huntington.

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:28.000
At first I just was part time and I started figuring out, gee it's going to take me 10. Well, the year is to finish.

00:26:28.000 --> 00:26:40.000
If I'm away from home and I have helped with the children and the housework I said I might as well go full time. So I did and I finished five years.

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:52.000
Yeah, I remember the time when the marchers were staying in our house. I felt kind of bad because we didn't know when they would be getting in at night.

00:26:52.000 --> 00:27:06.000
I left them on their own to prepare their food and I thought oh my goodness, you know why wasn't I m all in the hospital. But you know I had exams, I had kids.

00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:17.000
I don't know how I was young, they're young in my early 20s and I just thought we were providing a floor for them to sleep on.

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:25.000
I know we were feeding the army, you know, but anyway it was an interesting experience.

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:31.000
Did you have a sense of a historical significance of the event at the town?

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:59.000
I don't know, I don't know that I understood the significance of it until after we left Montgomery until later when I became aware of more and more activities.

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:21.000
Albany Movement jail was jailed right here in Americus, Georgia. He was like a hot potato, you know, they quickly got him down to a 40 miles south of here and put him in Albany Movement jail.

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:29.000
He was left during the Albany protests, so that's where he was brought during the Albany movement protests I think probably.

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:36.000
In December 61 there were a lot of arrests in Albany and they moved to all the different counties.

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:41.000
Could have been. He came from here down to Albany.

00:28:41.000 --> 00:28:51.000
I thought I understood that was the case. I wasn't here. This is just what I've heard.

00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:55.000
I've got people that we could check with to make sure.

00:28:55.000 --> 00:29:03.000
I think that was the case.

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:24.000
We didn't visit Koinonia Farm farm that had suffered a lot because of their activity as far as being very sympathetic to blacks in the area of the town.

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:35.000
They hated that there was so much poverty and injustice and the way the blacks were treated and so they befriended the blacks.

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:48.000
They all ate together the new meal and they were all kind of treated on the same social level and that's what got the local people so assated.

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:54.000
That was pretty much over by the time we moved here.

00:29:54.000 --> 00:30:08.000
After Millard raised the money to build that dormitory at Tougaloo College, we felt called to come back south and move to Koinonia Farm to work with Clarence Jordan and the other people that were there.

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:23.000
The violence had subsided. It's a fascinating history that I wish we had time to go into.

00:30:23.000 --> 00:30:38.000
As I mentioned, there's an excellent documentary, our long documentary that our daughter made and was aired on public television all over the country,

00:30:38.000 --> 00:30:45.000
and we had a lot of fires in the cotton patch so that pretty much tells that story.

00:30:45.000 --> 00:30:54.000
We had four kids, we were starting to build houses, we had partnership farming, we had partnership industries.

00:30:54.000 --> 00:31:08.000
We had pretty much a stretch just to live at Koinonia Farm and be a part of the things that would actually help black people in society there.

00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:16.000
That's part of what happened with civil rights too, the material things that wasn't just leak-old.

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:26.000
Maybe you could give a brief summary of what Clarence Jordan was and a short one.

00:31:27.000 --> 00:31:37.000
Okay, basically when we moved there, we got to know a lot of families that were living in Shacks.

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:49.000
Koinonia Farm had befriended these people over the years and helped them out in various ways, but the housing was just so strikingly poor.

00:31:49.000 --> 00:32:00.000
A lot of these houses were on the farms and part of the whole system.

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:03.000
My mind's blanking up.

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:07.000
The sharecropper system, thank you.

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:18.000
We would visit some of these Shacks and there were big holes in the roofs, holes in the floors.

00:32:18.000 --> 00:32:24.000
Newspapers had been tacked up on the walls to insulate as best as they could.

00:32:24.000 --> 00:32:32.000
When this were broken out, of course there was no attempt by the farmers to fix the houses.

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:42.000
But we had some property at Koinonia Farm and we said, well why don't we start what we call a partnership housing movement.

00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:46.000
We're in partnership with the people that need the help.

00:32:46.000 --> 00:32:55.000
We're in partnership with God who has given us the direction to help our brothers and sisters in need.

00:32:56.000 --> 00:33:14.000
Since Blacks could not go to the bank to get loans for to buy house or even by land, we thought well we'll just dedicate some of the land here, the 2000 something acres at Koinonia Farm, and start building houses.

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:22.000
Sell them to the families, no profit, no interest, that was the only way the families could afford it.

00:33:22.000 --> 00:33:29.000
And they were simple houses like the ones that we started off building or Cinder block.

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:38.000
For the first time, families had an indoor bathroom running water, things we just take for granted.

00:33:38.000 --> 00:33:44.000
Closet, kitchen cabinets.

00:33:44.000 --> 00:33:50.000
Wow, we saw it makes such a difference in the families.

00:33:50.000 --> 00:33:58.000
You know, for the Johnson family was the first family to get to move in to one of the houses.

00:33:58.000 --> 00:34:05.000
And then there were families after families that moved in.

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:17.000
Our remember we kind of hit a point where there were about 10 houses, 10 families moved in, and there were little kids running all over the neighborhood.

00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:22.000
You know, we had to play ground for them and a lot of them didn't even know what their names were.

00:34:22.000 --> 00:34:26.000
Their grandmama's were taking care of them.

00:34:26.000 --> 00:34:35.000
So, since my degree was in elementary education, we set up a child development center there.

00:34:35.000 --> 00:34:38.000
So one thing kind of just led to the other.

00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:43.000
And then we noticed that blacks didn't have, well they were either unemployed or under employed.

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:46.000
So we started partnership industries.

00:34:46.000 --> 00:34:50.000
Not only did we have the Peacond plant.

00:34:50.000 --> 00:34:56.000
And growing peanuts and corn.

00:34:56.000 --> 00:35:13.000
But we had, we started sewing industry and a pottery so that we could give employment to people that were making such low income.

00:35:13.000 --> 00:35:16.000
That's pretty much it in a nutshell.

00:35:16.000 --> 00:35:22.000
We lived at Koinonia Farm for five years to develop these types of things.

00:35:22.000 --> 00:35:28.000
But the thing that really interested us the most was the housing component.

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:35.000
That's what really seemed to make a difference in the lives of poor black people.

00:35:35.000 --> 00:35:39.000
Did you idea about that developed through the experience with all these programs?

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:44.000
I mean, the teaching of the housing and the child development and economic development.

00:35:44.000 --> 00:35:49.000
And so out of all of that, out of that experience that you focused in on the housing?

00:35:49.000 --> 00:35:50.000
On the housing.

00:35:50.000 --> 00:36:00.000
And we became interested in seeing if that same philosophy, that same, those same principles would work.

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:02.000
Outside the U.S.

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:09.000
We moved to Africa. We took our whole family to Africa for three years and pioneered the work there.

00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:12.000
Same thing.

00:36:12.000 --> 00:36:19.000
No profit, no interest, long term to pay, 20 years to pay.

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:21.000
And it worked there.

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:24.000
We came home after building about 120 houses.

00:36:24.000 --> 00:36:30.000
It took us about a year and a half to get the concrete block factory running.

00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:32.000
The first house built.

00:36:32.000 --> 00:36:36.000
But it was a tremendous success.

00:36:36.000 --> 00:36:38.000
And when we came home.

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:46.000
See, we've been raising support from churches, individuals, Koinonia Farm put some money into it.

00:36:46.000 --> 00:36:52.000
Companies like Lilly (Foundation) had given us a grant to buy concrete.

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:59.000
And so when we came back home, we thought, gee, you know, this idea probably worked most anywhere in the world.

00:36:59.000 --> 00:37:01.000
Where there's poverty.

00:37:01.000 --> 00:37:13.000
And we came back with the thought that we would start a worldwide ministry right at Koinonia Farm.

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:16.000
But things had changed a little bit.

00:37:16.000 --> 00:37:17.000
The leadership.

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:21.000
And they said, no, we just want to build houses right here in Sumter County.

00:37:21.000 --> 00:37:24.000
We don't want to do this whole big worldwide thing.

00:37:24.000 --> 00:37:28.000
So they gave us part of a chicken barn.

00:37:28.000 --> 00:37:31.000
We had a little desk and telephone.

00:37:31.000 --> 00:37:38.000
And we eventually named what we were doing, Habitat for Humanity International.

00:37:38.000 --> 00:37:40.000
A move into town.

00:37:40.000 --> 00:37:45.000
We needed to make a living, Millard (Dean) Fuller set up a law office.

00:37:45.000 --> 00:37:49.000
And Habitat, he and I, with mom and pop, you know.

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:55.000
And then, telephone systems were very unsophisticated.

00:37:55.000 --> 00:38:00.000
We had one phone on each of our desk for Habitat and another phone for the law office.

00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:07.000
And I had to remember, you know, fuller law office or Habitat for Humanity.

00:38:07.000 --> 00:38:17.000
But that gave us the foundation to involve volunteers and grow Habitat for Humanity International over the next 30 years

00:38:17.000 --> 00:38:20.000
to the point where we were in 100 countries.

00:38:20.000 --> 00:38:23.000
And it built houses for more than a million people.

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:26.000
That's remarkable.

00:38:26.000 --> 00:38:27.000
I want to go back.

00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:33.000
What was the Koinonia Farm community like when you moved into the community?

00:38:33.000 --> 00:38:37.000
I knew you said it had changed in a couple of times.

00:38:37.000 --> 00:38:40.000
And then, and we were also talking before we went on film.

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:43.000
And you were telling me about what it was like when you were coming to town,

00:38:43.000 --> 00:38:45.000
when you were living out there.

00:38:45.000 --> 00:38:48.000
And I'd love to hear more about those things.

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:49.000
Okay.

00:38:49.000 --> 00:38:55.000
When we moved to Koinonia Farm in the summer of 1968,

00:38:55.000 --> 00:38:57.000
there were very few people at Koinonia Farm.

00:38:57.000 --> 00:39:02.000
In fact, Clarence Jordan and his wife,

00:39:02.000 --> 00:39:06.000
well, they had one son still at home.

00:39:06.000 --> 00:39:13.000
They were exploring other places to go because Koinonia Farm had gotten to a real low-add.

00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:16.000
There was only one other family there.

00:39:16.000 --> 00:39:19.000
There were a few blacks living there.

00:39:19.000 --> 00:39:26.000
But Clarence was feeling that the work was over there.

00:39:26.000 --> 00:39:31.000
And he would just go teach in a seminary or something like that.

00:39:31.000 --> 00:39:34.000
But then when we wrote to him,

00:39:34.000 --> 00:39:36.000
well, actually Millard (Dean) Fuller wrote him,

00:39:36.000 --> 00:39:39.000
jotted him a little note when he was flying to a speaking gauge,

00:39:39.000 --> 00:39:40.000
a engagement.

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:44.000
And he said, Clarence, I'm thinking about leaving Tougaloo College.

00:39:44.000 --> 00:39:46.000
My work is almost done.

00:39:46.000 --> 00:39:49.000
What have you got up your sleeve?

00:39:49.000 --> 00:39:53.000
So Clarence wrote back and said,

00:39:53.000 --> 00:39:55.000
well, I don't have anything at my sleeve,

00:39:55.000 --> 00:39:58.000
but maybe God has something up his sleeve for both of us.

00:39:58.000 --> 00:40:01.000
So they got together at a church in Atlanta

00:40:01.000 --> 00:40:04.000
where Clarence was speaking a revival,

00:40:04.000 --> 00:40:07.000
our series of sermons.

00:40:07.000 --> 00:40:11.000
And Clarence would preach at night,

00:40:11.000 --> 00:40:14.000
and then Millard (Dean) Fuller and Clarence would talk during the day.

00:40:14.000 --> 00:40:17.000
And they explored all kinds of possibilities.

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:21.000
The idea was sort of to bring us to move down to Koinonia Farm

00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:26.000
and then maybe move to Atlanta to start some ministries.

00:40:26.000 --> 00:40:28.000
But the more we thought about it,

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:31.000
and we brought in a group of friends,

00:40:31.000 --> 00:40:34.000
a variety of people, pastors, business people,

00:40:34.000 --> 00:40:37.000
and brainstorm one big weekend.

00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:42.000
And they came up with the idea of this,

00:40:42.000 --> 00:40:45.000
they named it Koinonia Farm Partnership.

00:40:45.000 --> 00:40:48.000
And we would experiment with partnership,

00:40:48.000 --> 00:40:50.000
housing, partnership, industry,

00:40:50.000 --> 00:40:52.000
partnership farming,

00:40:52.000 --> 00:40:57.000
putting the disenfranchised people with more skills

00:40:57.000 --> 00:41:03.000
and more able people to build up society

00:41:03.000 --> 00:41:08.000
and give people a chance they didn't ever have a chance.

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:11.000
So yeah, we...

00:41:11.000 --> 00:41:18.000
If you go out there to Koinonia Farm,

00:41:18.000 --> 00:41:22.000
you would see that it's very simple lifestyle.

00:41:22.000 --> 00:41:26.000
And most of the places for families

00:41:26.000 --> 00:41:28.000
are just very small,

00:41:28.000 --> 00:41:35.000
lab-board houses that were built by volunteers over the years.

00:41:35.000 --> 00:41:40.000
And so we actually moved into the apartment upstairs

00:41:40.000 --> 00:41:43.000
that Clarence and Florence had lived at.

00:41:43.000 --> 00:41:46.000
It was one of the first structures that they had built

00:41:46.000 --> 00:41:48.000
back in the forties.

00:41:48.000 --> 00:41:53.000
And I'll never forget when my mother and daddy came

00:41:53.000 --> 00:41:55.000
for their first visit.

00:41:55.000 --> 00:41:58.000
You know, they were accustomed to visiting us

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:02.000
in this big 13-room house in Montgomery, Alabama

00:42:02.000 --> 00:42:05.000
with luxury cars and all this kind of stuff.

00:42:05.000 --> 00:42:08.000
And they climbed up these riggedy old stairs

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:10.000
and walked into my kitchen.

00:42:10.000 --> 00:42:13.000
I thought my mother was going to faint, she said.

00:42:13.000 --> 00:42:19.000
Oh, no, no progress in three generations.

00:42:19.000 --> 00:42:23.000
Oh my goodness.

00:42:23.000 --> 00:42:30.000
I don't think they really ever caught on their significance.

00:42:30.000 --> 00:42:38.000
We were having so much richer a life there at Koinonia Farm

00:42:38.000 --> 00:42:44.000
without all the glitz and glimmer materialistic kind of things.

00:42:44.000 --> 00:42:49.000
But I don't think they ever appreciated it.

00:42:49.000 --> 00:42:52.000
That's probably 60 seconds.

00:42:52.000 --> 00:42:55.000
Okay.

00:42:55.000 --> 00:42:59.000
And then, oh, yeah.

00:42:59.000 --> 00:43:05.000
So I don't think they ever really appreciated our new lifestyle,

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:07.000
new focus online.

00:43:07.000 --> 00:43:10.000
But to us, it was just thrilling.

00:43:10.000 --> 00:43:16.000
We felt like we were on the cutting edge of something really significant.

00:43:16.000 --> 00:43:23.000
And I mostly did work in the office

00:43:23.000 --> 00:43:27.000
with the peacon orders and the mailing list.

00:43:27.000 --> 00:43:31.000
And interface with a, we were having,

00:43:31.000 --> 00:43:35.000
like I say, it was very a small group of people

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:37.000
that were there when we moved there.

00:43:37.000 --> 00:43:41.000
But very quickly with these new initiatives,

00:43:41.000 --> 00:43:43.000
volunteers were coming in.

00:43:43.000 --> 00:43:48.000
And a lot of them from the north, it was the hippie movement, you know.

00:43:48.000 --> 00:43:51.000
Long hair, tattered jeans.

00:43:51.000 --> 00:43:58.000
And it was a time when people were questioning institutions

00:43:58.000 --> 00:44:04.000
and the way things were done traditionally.

00:44:04.000 --> 00:44:08.000
And they felt real challenged there

00:44:08.000 --> 00:44:12.000
and getting new direction on what was really right

00:44:12.000 --> 00:44:17.000
and getting their lives sort of at a point

00:44:17.000 --> 00:44:19.000
that they felt more comfortable,

00:44:19.000 --> 00:44:22.000
where they could move forward into society.

00:44:22.000 --> 00:44:25.000
But we would go into town.

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:28.000
I remember nobody had a car.

00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:29.000
We shared cars.

00:44:29.000 --> 00:44:30.000
We had to reserve a car.

00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:32.000
We wanted to go into town.

00:44:32.000 --> 00:44:35.000
But we would shop, you know, in the grocery stores.

00:44:35.000 --> 00:44:39.000
And people would look at me and they'd say,

00:44:39.000 --> 00:44:42.000
you're new here in town, aren't you?

00:44:42.000 --> 00:44:45.000
And I'd say, yes, well, where do you live?

00:44:45.000 --> 00:44:48.000
And when I said, Koinonia, you know,

00:44:48.000 --> 00:44:51.000
it was like they couldn't get it away from me fast enough.

00:44:51.000 --> 00:44:54.000
It was like, I was a lipper.

00:44:54.000 --> 00:44:59.000
And I experienced that time after time.

00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:02.000
But it didn't bother me a whole lot

00:45:02.000 --> 00:45:05.000
because I knew we were doing the right thing.

00:45:05.000 --> 00:45:08.000
And I felt sorry for them that they misunderstood.

00:45:08.000 --> 00:45:11.000
And our didn't understand, you know,

00:45:11.000 --> 00:45:16.000
what the true nature of what we were doing.

00:45:16.000 --> 00:45:18.000
We never were beat up.

00:45:18.000 --> 00:45:21.000
But before we were there, back in the 50s,

00:45:21.000 --> 00:45:23.000
there were residents.

00:45:23.000 --> 00:45:25.000
Koinonia, it would beat up.

00:45:25.000 --> 00:45:29.000
I can remember hearing about a story of Conrad Browne

00:45:29.000 --> 00:45:32.000
was walking down the street with a guy.

00:45:32.000 --> 00:45:35.000
And they were sharing a bag of peanut.

00:45:35.000 --> 00:45:39.000
Walking with one of the black residents of Koinonia.

00:45:39.000 --> 00:45:41.000
And they were both arrested.

00:45:41.000 --> 00:45:43.000
They were arrested.

00:45:43.000 --> 00:45:46.000
You know, that was just a no-no to be walking down the street,

00:45:46.000 --> 00:45:49.000
sharing a bag of peanuts.

00:45:49.000 --> 00:45:54.000
Now, we did have a pretty harrowing experience.

00:45:54.000 --> 00:45:57.000
There was a young man, a family,

00:45:57.000 --> 00:45:59.000
in Unadilla, Georgia.

00:45:59.000 --> 00:46:03.000
That's about 30, 40 miles east of here,

00:46:03.000 --> 00:46:08.000
just across the interstate, 75.

00:46:08.000 --> 00:46:14.000
And this young man wanted to be a doctor, a physician.

00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:17.000
And he knew that going to black school,

00:46:17.000 --> 00:46:20.000
the schools were still segregated at that time.

00:46:20.000 --> 00:46:24.000
He knew that the education he was getting in his school

00:46:24.000 --> 00:46:28.000
was it going to ever get him into med school?

00:46:28.000 --> 00:46:35.000
So he challenged the system in that rural town.

00:46:35.000 --> 00:46:40.000
I wanted to get into the high school, the white high school.

00:46:40.000 --> 00:46:43.000
And boy, that hit the news.

00:46:43.000 --> 00:46:46.000
We heard about it.

00:46:46.000 --> 00:46:49.000
It was on TV and the newspapers.

00:46:49.000 --> 00:46:54.000
And we decided that we needed to go over there

00:46:54.000 --> 00:46:57.000
and show some support to the family.

00:46:57.000 --> 00:47:03.000
And encourage them, you know, that what they were doing was right.

00:47:03.000 --> 00:47:06.000
So Millard and I and Faith, little Faith,

00:47:06.000 --> 00:47:08.000
she was still in diapers.

00:47:08.000 --> 00:47:11.000
She's the one that did the documentary on Cornania.

00:47:11.000 --> 00:47:14.000
And when you book that up, you see that.

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:15.000
Okay.

00:47:15.000 --> 00:47:17.000
Yes, to see what it is.

00:47:17.000 --> 00:47:18.000
Yeah.

00:47:18.000 --> 00:47:21.000
This is an hour-long documentary entitled,

00:47:21.000 --> 00:47:24.000
Briars in the Cotton Patch,

00:47:24.000 --> 00:47:31.000
Our daughter, Faith Fuller, produced back in the early 2000.

00:47:31.000 --> 00:47:40.000
It was released in 2003 and she's just done a 10th anniversary update of Briars.

00:47:40.000 --> 00:47:46.000
And it's been shown on public television in every state of the nation.

00:47:46.000 --> 00:47:49.000
And it's shown during times like Black History,

00:47:49.000 --> 00:47:51.000
things like that.

00:47:51.000 --> 00:47:56.000
She realized as an adult that the story of Cornania,

00:47:56.000 --> 00:48:00.000
here's a picture of Clarence Jordan right here,

00:48:00.000 --> 00:48:07.000
with a bunch of peanuts that he just got out of the field.

00:48:07.000 --> 00:48:13.000
She realized that the story had never really been told to the...

00:48:13.000 --> 00:48:17.000
There had been books written,

00:48:17.000 --> 00:48:20.000
articles and newspapers and magazines,

00:48:20.000 --> 00:48:26.000
but there never had been a significant documentary of that story.

00:48:26.000 --> 00:48:31.000
And she took it on herself to produce this documentary.

00:48:31.000 --> 00:48:33.000
She had never done a documentary before.

00:48:33.000 --> 00:48:35.000
It took her about three years.

00:48:35.000 --> 00:48:38.000
And she did the research.

00:48:38.000 --> 00:48:41.000
She raised the money.

00:48:41.000 --> 00:48:46.000
As I recall, she needed about $50,000 to do all that it needed.

00:48:46.000 --> 00:48:51.000
As you probably understand, a lot of people understand.

00:48:51.000 --> 00:48:58.000
It takes a lot of things other than just filming and editing film

00:48:58.000 --> 00:49:01.000
and actually producing a film.

00:49:01.000 --> 00:49:09.000
It is a lot that has to take place along with that.

00:49:09.000 --> 00:49:13.000
So we're very proud that she did that.

00:49:13.000 --> 00:49:18.000
What was the story of Clarence before you went there?

00:49:18.000 --> 00:49:23.000
It was founded by Clarence and Florence Jordan.

00:49:23.000 --> 00:49:27.000
And Martin and Mabel England,

00:49:27.000 --> 00:49:30.000
who only stayed about two or three years, I guess.

00:49:30.000 --> 00:49:32.000
But they were there in the very beginning.

00:49:32.000 --> 00:49:38.000
They basically started out with a poor plot of land.

00:49:38.000 --> 00:49:41.000
You know, red Georgia clay.

00:49:41.000 --> 00:49:47.000
And Clarence, being a graduate of the University of Georgia in agriculture,

00:49:47.000 --> 00:49:49.000
he loved farming.

00:49:49.000 --> 00:49:59.000
And so he thought that, you know, that would be a good venue to start an intentional Christian community

00:49:59.000 --> 00:50:04.000
to live out the teachings of Jesus.

00:50:04.000 --> 00:50:07.000
That he had studied about in seminary,

00:50:07.000 --> 00:50:12.000
it's Southern Baptist Theological Seminary in Louisville, Kentucky.

00:50:12.000 --> 00:50:16.000
He felt very strongly about this because having grown up

00:50:16.000 --> 00:50:20.000
in a small South Georgia town,

00:50:20.000 --> 00:50:25.000
Talbotton, Georgia, he saw the discrimination.

00:50:25.000 --> 00:50:28.000
He had friends, little black friends,

00:50:28.000 --> 00:50:32.000
that he could play with, but they couldn't go in his house, for instance.

00:50:32.000 --> 00:50:35.000
They couldn't go in his school.

00:50:35.000 --> 00:50:41.000
He saw the restrictions there on his little friends at a very early age

00:50:41.000 --> 00:50:47.000
and he began to question, you know, whether that was right or wrong.

00:50:47.000 --> 00:50:53.000
And then, of course, when he became a Greek New Testament scholar

00:50:53.000 --> 00:51:00.000
and read the original Greek, he could say that what he was reading,

00:51:00.000 --> 00:51:04.000
there didn't match up with the culture that he was raised in.

00:51:04.000 --> 00:51:11.000
And he wanted to experiment with these,

00:51:11.000 --> 00:51:20.000
what were pretty different principles.

00:51:20.000 --> 00:51:26.000
As you know, because that's why the Civil Rights Movement was generated

00:51:26.000 --> 00:51:30.000
because of all the injustices.

00:51:30.000 --> 00:51:37.000
And it was, the first few years

00:51:37.000 --> 00:51:41.000
were pretty much establishing the farm, getting housing.

00:51:41.000 --> 00:51:45.000
I know that Florence and Clarence had just a baby.

00:51:45.000 --> 00:51:50.000
And she lived with his parents in Tauberton

00:51:50.000 --> 00:51:53.000
first couple of years because there was no running water.

00:51:53.000 --> 00:52:01.000
I mean, it would been very difficult for them to have her and her children there.

00:52:01.000 --> 00:52:08.000
But, you know, they established the traditions of a Christian community,

00:52:08.000 --> 00:52:12.000
sharing the noon meals.

00:52:12.000 --> 00:52:16.000
Well, actually, I think they shared lunch and dinner at that time,

00:52:16.000 --> 00:52:19.000
the meal in common in the dining room.

00:52:19.000 --> 00:52:23.000
They held worship services and all of it was done,

00:52:23.000 --> 00:52:26.000
very simple structures.

00:52:26.000 --> 00:52:30.000
There was no actual church building.

00:52:30.000 --> 00:52:34.000
In fact, Clarence said that a guy came along

00:52:34.000 --> 00:52:39.000
and his catalog, one day Clarence, he was a very good mechanic too.

00:52:39.000 --> 00:52:44.000
He was, happened to be under a tractor, repairing a motor

00:52:44.000 --> 00:52:47.000
and it was all greasy, our barrels and things like that.

00:52:48.000 --> 00:52:53.000
So, he got up, you know, out of front of the tractor

00:52:53.000 --> 00:52:57.000
and kind of wiped off his hands and extended for a handshake

00:52:57.000 --> 00:53:04.000
and said, then the guy said, I'm out here.

00:53:04.000 --> 00:53:11.000
I want to see if you are really a Christian community like you say you are

00:53:11.000 --> 00:53:13.000
and I don't see a church anywhere.

00:53:13.000 --> 00:53:16.000
You couldn't be a Christian community.

00:53:16.000 --> 00:53:20.000
She's a little child.

00:53:20.000 --> 00:53:26.000
Where did the other families and other people who ended up living

00:53:26.000 --> 00:53:30.000
at Koinonia Farm come from? Were they local to the area or did most people

00:53:30.000 --> 00:53:31.000
come from outside?

00:53:31.000 --> 00:53:33.000
Most people came from outside.

00:53:33.000 --> 00:53:38.000
I think it was kind of rare for us to be southerners and live there.

00:53:38.000 --> 00:53:42.000
Is that true of the black families as well as the world?

00:53:42.000 --> 00:53:45.000
Most of the black families were local.

00:53:45.000 --> 00:53:48.000
They were from that county, pretty much.

00:53:48.000 --> 00:53:53.000
One of the reasons why it had gotten down to such small numbers

00:53:53.000 --> 00:54:00.000
when we moved there in 1968 is because the black families were threatened.

00:54:00.000 --> 00:54:06.000
Now, some kind of organized and moved up North.

00:54:06.000 --> 00:54:11.000
New York, I think, they established another Koinonia Farm community

00:54:11.000 --> 00:54:14.000
in the North, but I think it kind of fizzled out after a while.

00:54:14.000 --> 00:54:20.000
But the black families that stayed, they were threatened to the point

00:54:20.000 --> 00:54:24.000
where they said, if you continue to go to Koinonia Farm,

00:54:24.000 --> 00:54:27.000
we're going to burn your house down.

00:54:27.000 --> 00:54:32.000
Are we going to kill members of your family?

00:54:32.000 --> 00:54:35.000
I mean, really serious threats.

00:54:35.000 --> 00:54:43.000
And the lady who worked in the candy kitchen at Koinonia Farm,

00:54:43.000 --> 00:54:49.000
Miss Gussie Jackson, this happened way before we moved there.

00:54:49.000 --> 00:54:53.000
But they threatened to burn her house down and they did.

00:54:53.000 --> 00:54:55.000
They set it on fire.

00:54:55.000 --> 00:54:58.000
And she was at home at the time.

00:54:58.000 --> 00:55:02.000
And she went running out and fell on her knees

00:55:02.000 --> 00:55:06.000
and prayed to God to put out that fire.

00:55:06.000 --> 00:55:09.000
And it went out.

00:55:09.000 --> 00:55:17.000
But I don't know that they were ever successful in burning down

00:55:17.000 --> 00:55:24.000
any of the houses, but it scared people so badly that they kind of just drifted away.

00:55:24.000 --> 00:55:27.000
And this is in the 50s and 60s, but we...

00:55:27.000 --> 00:55:30.000
Yeah, I would say late 50s.

00:55:31.000 --> 00:55:35.000
So are most of the black families that were involved with Koinonia Farm

00:55:35.000 --> 00:55:38.000
didn't live on the properties?

00:55:38.000 --> 00:55:40.000
Some did, some didn't.

00:55:40.000 --> 00:55:47.000
Some still worked for farmers doing the seasonal crops.

00:55:47.000 --> 00:55:51.000
And then in the winter time when we needed help in the

00:55:51.000 --> 00:55:59.000
fru-cake candy kitchen, they would come and have temporary employment there.

00:56:00.000 --> 00:56:06.000
But by the time we got there, there were still people that were afraid to associate

00:56:06.000 --> 00:56:08.000
too closely with Koinonia Farm.

00:56:08.000 --> 00:56:13.000
As long as they just were going there for a job, it was kind of different.

00:56:13.000 --> 00:56:16.000
Yeah.

00:56:16.000 --> 00:56:22.000
And a few would come and join us for a community lunch sometimes.

00:56:22.000 --> 00:56:28.000
But they were still nervous about those threats

00:56:28.000 --> 00:56:31.000
that were made years earlier.

00:56:31.000 --> 00:56:34.000
You said you were telling a story about a...

00:56:34.000 --> 00:56:39.000
You said a harrowing experience where the black student and you needed...

00:56:39.000 --> 00:56:43.000
Oh, I never did finish that story, did I?

00:56:43.000 --> 00:56:45.000
And you needed Della.

00:56:45.000 --> 00:56:48.000
You needed Della, Georgia.

00:56:48.000 --> 00:56:49.000
Okay.

00:56:49.000 --> 00:56:50.000
So it was...

00:56:50.000 --> 00:56:53.000
It was about this time of year a little early.

00:56:53.000 --> 00:56:57.000
I remember there was an older guy that had a big strawberry patch.

00:56:57.000 --> 00:57:02.000
And we just picked bowls full of strawberries at morning.

00:57:02.000 --> 00:57:06.000
So we thought it'd be a nice thing to do to take the family some strawberries.

00:57:06.000 --> 00:57:09.000
So it was millered me and faith.

00:57:09.000 --> 00:57:10.000
Yeah, we...

00:57:10.000 --> 00:57:14.000
I know how we got side to act on wires in the cotton patch.

00:57:14.000 --> 00:57:18.000
So we get over there and we find the house.

00:57:18.000 --> 00:57:20.000
And no one was there.

00:57:20.000 --> 00:57:22.000
It was probably like about two o'clock.

00:57:22.000 --> 00:57:26.000
So we figured, well, she's off at work, forgotten the name of the family right?

00:57:26.000 --> 00:57:28.000
Now, but...

00:57:28.000 --> 00:57:31.000
And we figured, well, the kids are still at school.

00:57:31.000 --> 00:57:33.000
So we sat on the front porch.

00:57:33.000 --> 00:57:35.000
And pretty soon...

00:57:35.000 --> 00:57:43.000
A few of the children came home from school and they didn't know us from Adam's house cat.

00:57:43.000 --> 00:57:51.000
And so we talked to him and told him, well, we were there and kind of let him know that we were friendly.

00:57:52.000 --> 00:58:01.000
Well, the mother hadn't gotten home yet, but all of a sudden this police car comes roaring up.

00:58:01.000 --> 00:58:08.000
And the policeman got out of the car and he had his gun.

00:58:08.000 --> 00:58:12.000
And he said, what do you do in here at this nigger's house?

00:58:12.000 --> 00:58:17.000
And we said, well, we just came to visit.

00:58:17.000 --> 00:58:25.000
And he said, well, don't you know it's against the city ordinance for whites to visit with niggers?

00:58:25.000 --> 00:58:42.000
And we said, Miller said, he kind of a little smart alec, but he said, well, no, but if you have such an ordinance, you know, it's not worth the paper it's written on.

00:58:42.000 --> 00:58:47.000
Boy, did that make him mad and he said, okay, you're under arrest.

00:58:47.000 --> 00:58:50.000
And I was still up on the porch holding face in my arms.

00:58:50.000 --> 00:58:55.000
And Millard was down, you know, close to the policeman.

00:58:55.000 --> 00:59:06.000
And so I said to myself, I'm not going to let him take Millard off in the police car.

00:59:06.000 --> 00:59:11.000
And so I walked down and I said, if my husband was doing something wrong, I was too.

00:59:11.000 --> 00:59:15.000
You got to arrest me too.

00:59:15.000 --> 00:59:18.000
Yeah.

00:59:18.000 --> 00:59:23.000
Okay. So they took us down the city hall to the jail.

00:59:23.000 --> 00:59:25.000
And he said, okay, you sit over there.

00:59:25.000 --> 00:59:31.000
I'm going to call the city commissioner, county commissioner.

00:59:31.000 --> 00:59:34.000
We're going to have a meeting about this.

00:59:34.000 --> 00:59:37.000
So we sit there, we sit there.

00:59:37.000 --> 00:59:43.000
And I begin to think, oh my gosh, if they long to suck, what am I going to use for diapers?

00:59:43.000 --> 00:59:46.000
I mean, I didn't bring any extra diapers.

00:59:46.000 --> 00:59:50.000
I'm like, oh, I'm going to manage this.

00:59:50.000 --> 00:59:53.000
So we sat there and we sat there.

00:59:53.000 --> 00:59:56.000
And a faith was totalling around.

00:59:56.000 --> 00:59:59.000
There was a piano in there.

00:59:59.000 --> 01:00:04.000
And she walks over and you know, she starts playing the notes and I go, there's a shfake.

01:00:04.000 --> 01:00:06.000
We don't want to disturb them.

01:00:06.000 --> 01:00:11.000
Millard said, oh, let her go ahead and make all the noise she wants to.

01:00:11.000 --> 01:00:14.000
He was more ticked off than I was.

01:00:14.000 --> 01:00:19.000
Well, it wasn't long before they came out and they said, okay.

01:00:19.000 --> 01:00:24.000
So since this is only the first time you've done this, that we have recorded this,

01:00:24.000 --> 01:00:27.000
we're going to let you go for now.

01:00:27.000 --> 01:00:33.000
But, and I've millered her this, but I didn't really understand

01:00:33.000 --> 01:00:35.000
what they were saying.

01:00:35.000 --> 01:00:40.000
He said, but we're not responsible for you when you leave town.

01:00:40.000 --> 01:00:47.000
Miller read that, you know, they were going to come after us or try to do us harm.

01:00:47.000 --> 01:00:49.000
So they said, okay, you can go.

01:00:49.000 --> 01:00:51.000
They said, well, you brought us here.

01:00:51.000 --> 01:00:54.000
You got to take us back to our car.

01:00:54.000 --> 01:01:01.000
So we, Miller said, okay, he said, we're going to get out of here.

01:01:01.000 --> 01:01:05.000
We're going to go to the first motel that we can find and check in.

01:01:05.000 --> 01:01:12.000
And by the time we got there and registered and we're walking in our room,

01:01:12.000 --> 01:01:15.000
we saw a van pulling.

01:01:15.000 --> 01:01:19.000
It was full of men, we think.

01:01:19.000 --> 01:01:23.000
So we got in the motel room.

01:01:23.000 --> 01:01:25.000
I didn't know what to expect by then.

01:01:25.000 --> 01:01:28.000
So I took faith back into the bathroom.

01:01:28.000 --> 01:01:34.000
It was like your general motel rooms were the bathrooms all the way in the back.

01:01:34.000 --> 01:01:36.000
And I thought, they're going to start shooting us.

01:01:36.000 --> 01:01:38.000
Maybe that would be the safest place.

01:01:38.000 --> 01:01:40.000
Millard got on the phone.

01:01:40.000 --> 01:01:46.000
He called, he looked in the yellow pages at the churches.

01:01:46.000 --> 01:01:50.000
And so he, the first church he called was the Episcopal Church.

01:01:50.000 --> 01:01:54.000
He thought that maybe they would be the most sympathetic.

01:01:54.000 --> 01:02:00.000
And the, the, the, the director answered and Millard explained the situation

01:02:00.000 --> 01:02:04.000
that we may be in a threatening position.

01:02:04.000 --> 01:02:08.000
And would he come over and help us?

01:02:08.000 --> 01:02:18.000
And he said, oh, he said, I've promised the ladies that I would come and speak to their little tea this afternoon.

01:02:18.000 --> 01:02:21.000
I'm sorry, I cannot come.

01:02:21.000 --> 01:02:25.000
Well, then I think he called a couple more churches.

01:02:25.000 --> 01:02:27.000
There was no answer.

01:02:27.000 --> 01:02:35.000
So he thought, well, I'm going to take my chances and call a sheriff of this county.

01:02:35.000 --> 01:02:38.000
And see if he'll come.

01:02:38.000 --> 01:02:44.000
So apparently, he and the police chief weren't such good friends.

01:02:44.000 --> 01:02:46.000
So he did come over.

01:02:46.000 --> 01:02:50.000
And in fact, he got in touch with the FBI.

01:02:51.000 --> 01:02:56.000
Maybe they had had some incidents like this before.

01:02:56.000 --> 01:02:59.000
But he finally kind of calmed things down.

01:02:59.000 --> 01:03:05.000
We had called Clarence to come and get us to follow us home.

01:03:05.000 --> 01:03:10.000
And but it, it was kind of scary.

01:03:10.000 --> 01:03:14.000
Did, did, did, did Courtney come?

01:03:14.000 --> 01:03:16.000
Okay.

01:03:17.000 --> 01:03:24.000
You mentioned the back in Montgomery when Morris Dees and your husband were telling the clansmen

01:03:24.000 --> 01:03:26.000
that they weren't going to subscribe anymore.

01:03:26.000 --> 01:03:28.000
That they pulled the pistol out.

01:03:28.000 --> 01:03:29.000
And it pointed to me.

01:03:29.000 --> 01:03:31.000
Did any of the residents ever use self-defense?

01:03:31.000 --> 01:03:32.000
No.

01:03:32.000 --> 01:03:35.000
There were, there were no guns.

01:03:35.000 --> 01:03:39.000
I think they had one, I think Clarence had one gun in this house.

01:03:39.000 --> 01:03:45.000
But he would use it to like kill wild dogs or, you know, something like that.

01:03:45.000 --> 01:03:51.000
But they were totally against returning violence for violence.

01:03:51.000 --> 01:04:03.000
In fact, at one point when, when cars were riding by and shooting into the farm,

01:04:03.000 --> 01:04:08.000
sometimes bullets would narrowly escape kids that were playing outside.

01:04:08.000 --> 01:04:14.000
There were, there are still today some bullet holes that, in fact,

01:04:14.000 --> 01:04:19.000
the place where we were living, there was a bullet hole that came in and just barely

01:04:19.000 --> 01:04:22.000
miss one of the Jordan daughters.

01:04:22.000 --> 01:04:26.000
It shattered a mirror, but it missed her about inches.

01:04:26.000 --> 01:04:28.000
Nobody was ever killed.

01:04:28.000 --> 01:04:33.000
But they thought, well, you know, these are basically coward kind of folks.

01:04:33.000 --> 01:04:40.000
And they would take turns sitting out at the road at night.

01:04:40.000 --> 01:04:47.000
And just to demonstrate that they weren't afraid, and if they want to shoot,

01:04:47.000 --> 01:04:50.000
just go right ahead, you know.

01:04:50.000 --> 01:04:59.000
And there's a lot covered in the documentary, the Briars documentary about those kind of insinances

01:04:59.000 --> 01:05:01.000
and how the children felt about it.

01:05:01.000 --> 01:05:05.000
They were interviewed and a lot more detail on that.

01:05:05.000 --> 01:05:08.000
And it was a good thing to see them.

01:05:08.000 --> 01:05:12.000
Where did your children go to school when you moved here?

01:05:12.000 --> 01:05:15.000
That must have been an interesting situation.

01:05:15.000 --> 01:05:19.000
Well, we were out in the county and at that time, and for the longest time,

01:05:19.000 --> 01:05:23.000
until just recent years, there were two schools.

01:05:23.000 --> 01:05:25.000
There was county schools and city schools.

01:05:25.000 --> 01:05:31.000
So we were living in the county interestingly enough when we got, well,

01:05:31.000 --> 01:05:39.000
let me say this, when we first moved here, we only had two school-age kids,

01:05:39.000 --> 01:05:44.000
and they went to a little country school.

01:05:44.000 --> 01:05:49.000
And then we went away from to Africa.

01:05:49.000 --> 01:05:54.000
The oldest two were in an American school in Kinshasa, and that was wonderful.

01:05:54.000 --> 01:06:00.000
That was a much better education than they were receiving here.

01:06:00.000 --> 01:06:10.000
When we came back, we had three in public school, and our youngest child,

01:06:10.000 --> 01:06:15.000
who was born at Koinonia, went to the Child Development Center.

01:06:15.000 --> 01:06:19.000
That way it started before we left.

01:06:19.000 --> 01:06:24.000
And interestingly enough, the daughter, faith, that made the documentary,

01:06:24.000 --> 01:06:27.000
she was in class with Amy Carter.

01:06:27.000 --> 01:06:33.000
And it was right at the end of the Carter campaign that we came back from Africa.

01:06:33.000 --> 01:06:37.000
And faith and Amy were in fourth grade together.

01:06:37.000 --> 01:06:40.000
The school was over in planes.

01:06:40.000 --> 01:06:44.000
Of course, where the Carter still lived.

01:06:44.000 --> 01:06:52.000
Yeah, there was secret service in the class, and they allowed Amy to go climb a tree and read,

01:06:52.000 --> 01:06:56.000
rather than play on the playground.

01:06:56.000 --> 01:07:02.000
That was kind of interesting, but the older two, Chris and Kim, went to high school at planes.

01:07:02.000 --> 01:07:06.000
And they would come home from school, especially the daughter.

01:07:06.000 --> 01:07:14.000
It was in like ninth grade by this time, crying because the schools were just awful.

01:07:14.000 --> 01:07:20.000
These were white schools, but the building had become in such a disarray.

01:07:20.000 --> 01:07:24.000
It eventually became the Carter Museum in Plains.

01:07:24.000 --> 01:07:28.000
And a lot of restoration of that school took place.

01:07:28.000 --> 01:07:31.000
It's beautifully done now.

01:07:31.000 --> 01:07:34.000
That it was in horrible condition.

01:07:34.000 --> 01:07:39.000
Then I know that she complained about bird droppings coming from the ceiling.

01:07:39.000 --> 01:07:45.000
And the teachers would just pretty much let them look at magazines and not much instruction going on.

01:07:45.000 --> 01:07:48.000
The quality of the school's greatly improved.

01:07:48.000 --> 01:07:53.000
That's one of the things that encouraged us to move into town.

01:07:53.000 --> 01:07:58.000
The fact that Koinonia Farm really didn't want to be part of the worldwide movement.

01:07:58.000 --> 01:08:01.000
And then we needed better schools for our kids.

01:08:01.000 --> 01:08:06.000
We had better schools here in the city.

01:08:06.000 --> 01:08:18.000
So they got a really good education here when the schools were integrated.

01:08:18.000 --> 01:08:30.000
I'd say in the late 70s.

01:08:30.000 --> 01:08:36.000
The quality of education continued to be really good.

01:08:36.000 --> 01:08:42.000
And to the point where all of our kids went to college, finished college.

01:08:42.000 --> 01:08:47.000
There are complaints that the education kids are getting here.

01:08:47.000 --> 01:08:48.000
It's not adequate.

01:08:48.000 --> 01:08:52.000
But any kid that wants to go to college, we have an excellent college here in America.

01:08:52.000 --> 01:08:58.000
Because we have a big technical college.

01:08:58.000 --> 01:09:05.000
So even if, since we're a small town here, we have good quality education.

01:09:05.000 --> 01:09:10.000
So the schools didn't integrate here until the late 70s?

01:09:10.000 --> 01:09:12.000
I believe that's right.

01:09:12.000 --> 01:09:17.000
I don't think they were integrated when we first came back from Africa.

01:09:17.000 --> 01:09:21.000
I think it was pretty soon after that.

01:09:21.000 --> 01:09:27.000
I think it was nationally one of the big moments was around 1970.

01:09:27.000 --> 01:09:33.000
The Supreme Court decision was to cooperate separate schools in the same district.

01:09:33.000 --> 01:09:36.000
And I wondered if that had an impact around here.

01:09:36.000 --> 01:09:41.000
Well, it took a while.

01:09:41.000 --> 01:09:44.000
And it was pretty slowly.

01:09:44.000 --> 01:09:48.000
I could be wrong.

01:09:48.000 --> 01:09:53.000
I don't think they were integrated in 1976 when we came back from Africa.

01:09:53.000 --> 01:09:57.000
But I think it was a short time after that they were.

01:09:57.000 --> 01:10:02.000
Did you know much about the Civil Rights Movement in Americus after you moved here?

01:10:02.000 --> 01:10:05.000
Or did you hear much about it?

01:10:05.000 --> 01:10:10.000
Other than what the stories at Koinonia Farm.

01:10:10.000 --> 01:10:17.000
That was pretty much, I don't know if I should term it a hot spot.

01:10:17.000 --> 01:10:25.000
Or that was where a lot of transformation occurred at Koinonia Farm.

01:10:25.000 --> 01:10:34.000
I heard more about what happened in the general area.

01:10:34.000 --> 01:10:38.000
After we've been here a while, we have a wonderful historian.

01:10:38.000 --> 01:10:46.000
His name is Alan Anderson, who has studied the history of Sumter County, Georgia from the very beginning.

01:10:46.000 --> 01:10:49.000
And he wrote a book.

01:10:49.000 --> 01:10:54.000
He's got a lot of details about those kind of things.

01:10:54.000 --> 01:11:03.000
One of the things that Americus is kind of infamous for, I guess, is the little girls that were arrested and put in jail.

01:11:03.000 --> 01:11:06.000
This would have been before you were here.

01:11:06.000 --> 01:11:10.000
But I wondered if something like that was part of the...

01:11:10.000 --> 01:11:13.000
I met one of them.

01:11:13.000 --> 01:11:18.000
I can't remember her name, but I met one of them.

01:11:18.000 --> 01:11:20.000
You was arrested.

01:11:20.000 --> 01:11:22.000
Is that something that people in here?

01:11:22.000 --> 01:11:24.000
I'm also interested in historic memory.

01:11:24.000 --> 01:11:32.000
So I'm sort of wondering like how, you know, in the community that I grew up in, I'm sort of interested in how people understand the past.

01:11:32.000 --> 01:11:37.000
So I wonder if it's something that people around here think about or talk about more.

01:11:37.000 --> 01:11:40.000
I remember now where I met her.

01:11:40.000 --> 01:11:51.000
Koinonia had a celebration of the 70th anniversary of Koinonia.

01:11:51.000 --> 01:11:58.000
And people came from all over who had lived at Koinonia at one time or the other.

01:11:58.000 --> 01:12:03.000
And I met a lot of these folks that I'd heard stories about.

01:12:04.000 --> 01:12:07.000
Yeah, it was really interesting.

01:12:10.000 --> 01:12:18.000
Oh, I can tell you about an incident that happened in 1965 that I'd forgotten about.

01:12:18.000 --> 01:12:23.000
That was when we came to visit some friends of ours.

01:12:23.000 --> 01:12:31.000
He had been kicked out of his church in Birmingham, Alabama for proposing, you know, they should be more welcoming to black people.

01:12:32.000 --> 01:12:38.000
And so he was, he came over to Koinonia to live.

01:12:38.000 --> 01:12:44.000
I mean, they were just really out and know what to do.

01:12:44.000 --> 01:12:51.000
And so we, he had actually preached in our little church that we started in our home in Montgomery, Alabama.

01:12:51.000 --> 01:12:53.000
But we came to visit them.

01:12:53.000 --> 01:12:59.000
This was right after we decided to leave business and give away our money and we were looking for new direction.

01:13:00.000 --> 01:13:05.000
So we decided to look Allen and Carol Henry up, Carol and, and Allen Henry.

01:13:05.000 --> 01:13:09.000
And that's when we first met Clarence.

01:13:09.000 --> 01:13:17.000
And we were so amazed at, at, at Cornania and its history.

01:13:17.000 --> 01:13:25.000
And the simple lifestyle was appealing to us then because we were getting rid of all of our material possessions.

01:13:25.000 --> 01:13:31.000
We stayed a month, instead of two hours, we stayed a month.

01:13:31.000 --> 01:13:37.000
Yeah, and so that was December, almost all of December of 1965.

01:13:37.000 --> 01:13:49.000
Well, Carol and Allen Henry's father was head of the Georgia Baptist Convention, or, yeah, I think it was, that's what it was.

01:13:49.000 --> 01:14:03.000
And he had been invited to speak at a Christmas church service at night at first Baptist church in Americus, which was totally segregated.

01:14:03.000 --> 01:14:06.000
Just total white congregation.

01:14:06.000 --> 01:14:15.000
And so he came out to visit his daughter, had lunch with us and he said, you know, I'm preaching tonight.

01:14:15.000 --> 01:14:19.000
I want to invite all of you to come.

01:14:19.000 --> 01:14:22.000
Well, you know, here we were, an integrated group.

01:14:22.000 --> 01:14:29.000
And so we, we had a little discussion about that in the afternoon and Clarence said, well, we've been invited.

01:14:29.000 --> 01:14:32.000
We ought to go.

01:14:32.000 --> 01:14:33.000
Whoever wants to go.

01:14:33.000 --> 01:14:36.000
So we loaded up in several cars.

01:14:36.000 --> 01:14:38.000
They're probably about 20 of us.

01:14:38.000 --> 01:14:42.000
Clarence, Miller to me, Collins McGee.

01:14:42.000 --> 01:14:46.000
He was the only black person that would go with us.

01:14:46.000 --> 01:14:54.000
All the rest would, Allen, Carol and Allen Henry and some of the other residents of Koinonia Farm.

01:14:54.000 --> 01:14:58.000
So we started filing in.

01:14:58.000 --> 01:15:05.000
The big crowd was coming in to First Baptist church, on Leastry in America's sand.

01:15:05.000 --> 01:15:13.000
So we were kind of single file and the deacons were passing out programs for the service.

01:15:13.000 --> 01:15:26.000
And when a black hand reached out to take one of the programs, you know, it was like, what?

01:15:26.000 --> 01:15:34.000
But I mean things continued. We all got in and we occupied one full pew.

01:15:34.000 --> 01:15:42.000
And so we were settling in and there were several little ladies on the pew in front of us.

01:15:42.000 --> 01:15:47.000
And they looked back and they started whispering, you know, and they got up and they moved somewhere else.

01:15:47.000 --> 01:15:51.000
Same thing happened to the people that were seated behind us.

01:15:51.000 --> 01:15:54.000
They got up and moved somewhere else.

01:15:54.000 --> 01:16:01.000
So here we were like an island on this one pew in the church.

01:16:01.000 --> 01:16:10.000
And they started singing Christmas hymns.

01:16:10.000 --> 01:16:15.000
Oh gosh, what was that hymn we were singing?

01:16:15.000 --> 01:16:24.000
I don't think of it in a minute. Anyway, along comes the head deacon, who happened to be the fire chief in town.

01:16:24.000 --> 01:16:34.000
And he comes in and he grabs hold of Collins McGee and he said, you got to get out of here.

01:16:34.000 --> 01:16:38.000
And Clarence said, wait a minute, wait a minute, we were invited to come here.

01:16:38.000 --> 01:16:43.000
He said, you know, we're here to worship with you.

01:16:43.000 --> 01:16:46.000
I have to enjoy the service with you.

01:16:46.000 --> 01:16:52.000
And he said, that's beside the point. You can stay, but he's got to get out of here.

01:16:52.000 --> 01:16:55.000
You know, jerkin on Collins arm.

01:16:55.000 --> 01:16:58.000
And Clarence said, never mind, never mind.

01:16:58.000 --> 01:17:05.000
He said, if you don't want Collins here, we're going to all leave.

01:17:05.000 --> 01:17:09.000
So we all got up and we left.

01:17:09.000 --> 01:17:19.000
So there were a few deacons that came and talked to Clarence and Millard (Dean) Fuller and a few others and said,

01:17:19.000 --> 01:17:22.000
what are you doing bringing this nigger into our church?

01:17:22.000 --> 01:17:25.000
Don't you know that we don't allow that?

01:17:25.000 --> 01:17:32.000
And so Clarence said, well, sir, I thought this was God's church.

01:17:32.000 --> 01:17:35.000
And God is no respect to a person.

01:17:35.000 --> 01:17:43.000
He said, we didn't come here to do harm. He said, that's beside the point.

01:17:43.000 --> 01:17:46.000
The federal government doesn't own this church.

01:17:46.000 --> 01:17:49.000
We own this church.

01:17:49.000 --> 01:17:52.000
And so, you know, we left.

01:17:52.000 --> 01:17:56.000
And it was interesting as we walked out to the sidewalk.

01:17:56.000 --> 01:18:00.000
Clarence, I never will forget. I can remember seeing him do this today.

01:18:00.000 --> 01:18:03.000
He turned around and he looked at the church.

01:18:03.000 --> 01:18:06.000
Big white columns.

01:18:06.000 --> 01:18:12.000
And there were floodlights, you know, just beaming on this church building.

01:18:12.000 --> 01:18:17.000
And Clarence made the remark, just look at there.

01:18:17.000 --> 01:18:26.000
It's at all that light on the outside and it's dark on the inside.

01:18:26.000 --> 01:18:32.000
There were times when we lived at Koinonia Farm that groups came in.

01:18:32.000 --> 01:18:41.000
I have pictures of those incidences where we had black visitors that wanted to attend church in town.

01:18:41.000 --> 01:18:46.000
So Clarence and Millard (Dean) Fuller and a few others would go with them.

01:18:46.000 --> 01:18:52.000
But the deacons were armed during that time.

01:18:52.000 --> 01:18:56.000
Now, since then, there have been a huge change.

01:18:56.000 --> 01:19:02.000
Blacks are welcome in almost any church here in town.

01:19:02.000 --> 01:19:04.000
There have been a huge change.

01:19:04.000 --> 01:19:09.000
You know how that came about?

01:19:09.000 --> 01:19:17.000
Well, I guess the culture began to change as the old generation began to die off.

01:19:17.000 --> 01:19:20.000
Some of the laws changed.

01:19:20.000 --> 01:19:26.000
I mean, some of the poor, of course, couldn't really force churches to make that change.

01:19:26.000 --> 01:19:33.000
Clarence often says, you know, everything's integrated except the jails and the churches.

01:19:33.000 --> 01:19:37.000
And I have hope for the jails.

01:19:37.000 --> 01:19:45.000
Well, you know, it was just happened over time.

01:19:45.000 --> 01:20:01.000
I'd like to think that Habitat's Ministry developing here in Americus had something to do with it because we had people coming in from all over the United States.

01:20:01.000 --> 01:20:06.000
Some people from different countries in the world.

01:20:06.000 --> 01:20:13.000
I think it helped the broadened people's ideas of who guys' children were.

01:20:13.000 --> 01:20:18.000
How did the local community felt and feels about Habitat and the work that you were doing?

01:20:18.000 --> 01:20:29.000
Well, at first, you know, it was uncomfortable when we, I remember when we bought a house in town.

01:20:29.000 --> 01:20:35.000
On church street, we moved into town from Koinonia,

01:20:35.000 --> 01:20:42.000
And our kids started going out and playing with children in the neighborhood.

01:20:42.000 --> 01:20:52.000
And when they learned that we had moved into town from Koinonia, they didn't allow their kids to play with our kids anymore for a while.

01:20:52.000 --> 01:21:01.000
And we had broken glass on our driveway, most every morning when we would wake up and I'd just go out.

01:21:01.000 --> 01:21:04.000
So we could end my dust pan.

01:21:04.000 --> 01:21:10.000
But there were two tragedies that happened within a week after we moved in.

01:21:10.000 --> 01:21:26.000
One was a huge house that had been on the market that had just sold like a big three-story mansion of the house caught fire about a block down from where we lived.

01:21:26.000 --> 01:21:33.000
Millard (Dean) Fuller was away on a speaking engagement and I woke up during the night and I heard all these car doors slamming.

01:21:33.000 --> 01:21:36.000
Oh my goodness.

01:21:36.000 --> 01:21:44.000
Now, not only do we have broken glass on our driveway, but some actions being taken here.

01:21:44.000 --> 01:22:02.000
So I didn't turn on any lights. I tipped to the front window and looked out and we'd leave to see that these pickup trucks, people that were getting out of the pickup trucks, were hurrying down the street and then I looked and saw the big fire.

01:22:02.000 --> 01:22:09.000
So I breathed the sigh of relief there.

01:22:09.000 --> 01:22:12.000
But then word began to spread.

01:22:12.000 --> 01:22:17.000
You know, we were starting work kind of like what we had at Koinonia.

01:22:17.000 --> 01:22:26.000
That was in Americus, Georgia and some hippie kind of people were coming, you know, as volunteers.

01:22:26.000 --> 01:22:35.000
There was very little understanding of what we were trying to do to eradicate poverty housing.

01:22:35.000 --> 01:22:42.000
And there was some really bad areas. Most of the streets had not been paved.

01:22:42.000 --> 01:22:47.000
Just terrible shacks. And so, you know, we got organized.

01:22:47.000 --> 01:22:55.000
We not only started work here in Americus, but we were starting down in South Florida in Immokalee, Florida, where a lot of migrant workers were.

01:22:55.000 --> 01:23:00.000
We were starting work in Appalachia.

01:23:00.000 --> 01:23:05.000
Those were on Johns Island, South Carolina, where there was a lot of poverty.

01:23:05.000 --> 01:23:19.000
People were getting in touch with us because they had heard through Koinonia newsletters and newsletters that we were producing, you know, that we were spreading this on-dend, that we were willing to kind of help them get started.

01:23:19.000 --> 01:23:28.000
But I think there were two things that really changed and opened people's hearts here in Americus, Georgia.

01:23:28.000 --> 01:23:39.000
One was the...there were a lot of seniors, all ages that were coming here to help us, that were volunteers at Habitat.

01:23:39.000 --> 01:23:47.000
And they would go to the local churches and they would begin to explain, you know, what we were all about.

01:23:47.000 --> 01:24:00.000
Then when we started having blitzbills, like building 10, 20 houses in a week's time, and we had hundreds of people coming in to work on those projects.

01:24:00.000 --> 01:24:10.000
And we started involving the local churches, getting them to sponsor a half of a house, a few of them came out and volunteered.

01:24:10.000 --> 01:24:17.000
The idea began to catch on and people began to see really what we were all about.

01:24:17.000 --> 01:24:21.000
They were trying to put God's love and action to really help people.

01:24:21.000 --> 01:24:27.000
Were you able to get the first churches to locally to get on board?

01:24:27.000 --> 01:24:38.000
Well, some really nice people, mostly from up north, would start attending the churches.

01:24:38.000 --> 01:24:45.000
And they would make friends, and then they would invite their friends to come and participate that week.

01:24:45.000 --> 01:24:50.000
And, you know, a week, that was a very threatening, so they would do it.

01:24:50.000 --> 01:25:07.000
But I think the thing that really changed the climate and the business community, they saw where a lot of volunteers came and bought a lot of groceries, a lot of this and a lot of that.

01:25:07.000 --> 01:25:12.000
So it was a boost for the economy.

01:25:12.000 --> 01:25:18.000
Plus we were employing people too, permanent people, they were buying houses.

01:25:18.000 --> 01:25:32.000
And, you know, though the business people began to be more supportive, we were bringing, and our first year of habitat, we raised about 70,000 dollars.

01:25:33.000 --> 01:25:38.000
Nobody knew about it. You know, it was a real struggle in the early years.

01:25:38.000 --> 01:25:44.000
Before the Carters got involved, really, in 1984, it was real struggle to raise money.

01:25:44.000 --> 01:25:58.000
And then, right before we left habitat in 2005, commonly a quarter of a million or more dollars would come in every day.

01:25:59.000 --> 01:26:09.000
Every day, we had work in a hundred countries. We had over 900 employees. We were supporting too.

01:26:09.000 --> 01:26:12.000
We had headquarters offices.

01:26:12.000 --> 01:26:20.000
Yeah, yeah. And then after we left, the board made the decision to move habitat headquarters to Atlanta.

01:26:20.000 --> 01:26:23.000
So that must have had an impact on the Americus economy?

01:26:23.000 --> 01:26:29.000
And they said they had, they had to, unfortunately.

01:26:29.000 --> 01:26:33.000
When you were at one, excuse me.

01:26:33.000 --> 01:26:39.000
When you were do the Blitz builds, and so you'd have people come in for a week or something, where would they be staying?

01:26:39.000 --> 01:26:47.000
Oh, well, some of them stayed in private homes, and that kind of helped spread the word too.

01:26:47.000 --> 01:27:00.000
Sometimes they buck down in churches, or sometimes the college, where they were on break and made dormitory rooms available.

01:27:00.000 --> 01:27:05.000
So that helped to educate the community too, getting them involved.

01:27:05.000 --> 01:27:10.000
They could see what a difference it was making in the lives of families.

01:27:10.000 --> 01:27:20.000
We had started doing better in school. I remember I had a teacher told me we were in the grocery store.

01:27:20.000 --> 01:27:31.000
And she said, wow, she said, it's amazing the difference in the student in my class since they moved into a habitat house.

01:27:31.000 --> 01:27:37.000
They said it needs better behaved, making better grades.

01:27:37.000 --> 01:27:46.000
So it was those kind of experiences that helped people to see, that we were really on to something here.

01:27:46.000 --> 01:27:49.000
Yeah, that's what we found on the DC.

01:27:49.000 --> 01:27:52.000
It's a standard of living, yes.

01:27:52.000 --> 01:28:09.000
When you were talking about those discussions, I think in 1968, about what direction and when you moved to Koinonia Farm and developed the housing and economic development,

01:28:09.000 --> 01:28:15.000
it seemed like roughly at the same time, in that same era, there's a whole co-op movement going on.

01:28:15.000 --> 01:28:22.000
There's all sorts of programs that are probably coming out of the civil rights movement, probably related to the law and poverty.

01:28:22.000 --> 01:28:32.000
Are you part of these larger conversations? Is that influencing the thinking that you were all involved in at the time, and what you were doing?

01:28:32.000 --> 01:28:37.000
Well, certainly, we tried to keep our focus on housing.

01:28:37.000 --> 01:28:45.000
There were temptations to broaden our ministry into other areas.

01:28:45.000 --> 01:29:00.000
But we were certainly working side by side with other organizations, other efforts to build awareness of needs, of humanity.

01:29:00.000 --> 01:29:03.000
Not only here in the United States, but around the world.

01:29:03.000 --> 01:29:08.000
Where did your international interest come from?

01:29:08.000 --> 01:29:20.000
Well, our goal right from the beginning was to eliminate poverty housing in the world.

01:29:20.000 --> 01:29:28.000
Right after we had left Montgomery, left business, we decided that we wanted to visit missionaries in Africa.

01:29:28.000 --> 01:29:36.000
And we had the United Church of Christ, which was Millard (Dean) Fuller's Church that he raised in to arrange a tour.

01:29:36.000 --> 01:29:48.000
Actually, they had asked him to do this, to visit missionaries and come back and tell about what he saw, and to raise money and awareness of mission work.

01:29:48.000 --> 01:29:54.000
But he turned him down because he figured he'd cost him too much.

01:29:54.000 --> 01:29:59.000
It slowed him down on his first million of too much.

01:29:59.000 --> 01:30:05.000
So we decided that that was one of the first things we wanted to do.

01:30:05.000 --> 01:30:10.000
And it was a six week trip. We got grandparents to take care of our kids.

01:30:10.000 --> 01:30:18.000
We went to five countries in Africa. And as it turned out, we went back to one of the places we visited.

01:30:18.000 --> 01:30:21.000
Which countries did you go on that first?

01:30:21.000 --> 01:30:34.000
We went to Tanzania, what was Rhodesia (now Zimbabwe), South Africa, Ghana, and what was then the Congo.

01:30:34.000 --> 01:30:42.000
When we lived there in the 70s, it was Zaire. And now it's Congo again, Democratic and Public Congo.

01:30:42.000 --> 01:30:47.000
How did you decide to go back to Congo's Ayer?

01:30:47.000 --> 01:31:01.000
Well, you know, when we visited there, the church wanted to reinstitute a business that a Belgian business man had started.

01:31:01.000 --> 01:31:10.000
And somehow another church had acquired it. But the dump truck was worn out.

01:31:10.000 --> 01:31:20.000
And several other aspects of the concrete block business had just broken down.

01:31:20.000 --> 01:31:25.000
So Millard (Dean) Fuller promised that he would come back home and raise money to buy them a new dump truck.

01:31:25.000 --> 01:31:28.000
So we had that connection there.

01:31:28.000 --> 01:31:38.000
And so when we started thinking about where we could build houses, we thought of that place. You know what a perfect place.

01:31:38.000 --> 01:31:48.000
The church invited us to come and help with the economy of the people. And without, well, we'll just make concrete blocks and build houses.

01:31:48.000 --> 01:31:58.000
So it was just kind of a natural. Well, we feel like it was a God plan thing, you know, that evolved.

01:31:58.000 --> 01:32:04.000
How did it influence you to live outside the country for that long? You know, to take your children?

01:32:04.000 --> 01:32:14.000
Well, I don't know. I've always been at Ventressam. I told you that my parents were in the appliance business.

01:32:14.000 --> 01:32:21.000
And we went to Florida one week out of the year. And that's it. I didn't go anywhere out.

01:32:21.000 --> 01:32:30.000
So I was interested in seeing other parts of the world, that trip that we made.

01:32:30.000 --> 01:32:38.000
When I was 25 years old to Africa, it broadened my horizons a lot.

01:32:38.000 --> 01:32:51.000
And it just, and Millard (Dean) Fuller was adventurous too. You know, we had learned how to live simply, learn how to make yogurt, make bread, all these kind of things at Koinonia,

01:32:51.000 --> 01:32:58.000
So it was kind of a good training ground. Then a missionary plus my own simple upbringing.

01:32:58.000 --> 01:33:10.000
My mother taught me to have so into cook. We were good at surviving and most anywhere.

01:33:10.000 --> 01:33:18.000
We had this vision and any time we'd go to a new country, a new place, we'd read books.

01:33:18.000 --> 01:33:26.000
We tried to understand the culture. And we built what we called appropriate technologies. We used appropriate technologies.

01:33:26.000 --> 01:33:34.000
So to keep the cost of the houses down, whatever the style house, whatever materials were available in that area.

01:33:34.000 --> 01:33:43.000
And, you know, doing a lot of manual labor so that we wouldn't have machines breaking down.

01:33:43.000 --> 01:34:00.000
And we enjoyed visiting families that, in fact, many times we would stay with families that had moved into a habitat house, Sri Lanka, South Korea,

01:34:00.000 --> 01:34:11.000
and the Fiji. The family thought it was kind of interesting, you know, that the founders and the president and his wife of Habitat, for Humanity,

01:34:11.000 --> 01:34:18.000
would want to stay in their little humble abode. But we took great joy in that.

01:34:18.000 --> 01:34:30.000
Because that gave us inspiration to want to provide that for more and more families.

01:34:30.000 --> 01:34:38.000
I was just seeing those countries you listed. Some of those had just been through anti-colonial movements, sort of just sort of,

01:34:38.000 --> 01:34:49.000
and some were still colonial countries. Did you have a sense of that at the time? Or notice any differences?

01:34:49.000 --> 01:34:58.000
That's an interesting question. Of course, that was certainly the case in Zaire.

01:34:58.000 --> 01:35:16.000
In On Congo, the Belgians...", actually right at the time we visited for the first time in 1965.

01:35:16.000 --> 01:35:32.000
So it was still, because of the independence, you know, most of the Belgian business people had left the Catholic Church and foreign missionaries were there.

01:35:32.000 --> 01:35:48.000
But it was a time when a huge population had come into the cities to find work. They were now free. They didn't have to stay out of the city.

01:35:48.000 --> 01:36:01.000
They no longer had to have a card to move around. So they were just flooding into the cities which made the housing situation just overwhelming.

01:36:01.000 --> 01:36:17.000
We built 120 houses, but that was just a drop in the bucket. After we left, though, more and more, you know, more and more, it continued and it spread, you know, spread into other parts of Zaire and other African countries.

01:36:17.000 --> 01:36:39.000
Now, I guess that would also apply to South Africa. They were still, our partake was strong back in 1955. Also, when we started work there, but we started work in the townships, first of all.

01:36:39.000 --> 01:36:59.000
And there were other programs where there was job training and opportunities for people to start little micro industries and that way they could afford to make the payments for our habitat houses.

01:36:59.000 --> 01:37:10.000
So it was a way to liberate, get people out from underneath the oppression, just like we did at Cornania.

01:37:10.000 --> 01:37:33.000
We had farmers to come and I know we were just almost finished with a house, family about ready to move in. And here comes a farmer on his horse, it had rained and he just went round and round and round his horse and just made a mess of the bright yard. He was mad.

01:37:33.000 --> 01:38:01.000
And there was another instance where Ethel Dunning had worked in the kitchen, done housework for a farmer and his wife. And they found out that they were going to move, going to have a house with their own and move off of their farm and they cut off their water.

01:38:01.000 --> 01:38:22.000
They had to haul water in barrels for several months while their house was under construction. And to beat all that woman had enough nerve to come and ask Ethel to bake cakes for them at Christmas.

01:38:22.000 --> 01:38:27.000
She missed out on the lady.

01:38:27.000 --> 01:38:36.000
And they never turned her water back on. She asked them to, but they never did.

01:38:36.000 --> 01:38:51.000
Excuse me, but she told us she said, you know, I baked those cakes. She said, I had to show them that I was bigger than how I was being treated.

01:38:51.000 --> 01:38:54.000
But they never turned around.

01:38:54.000 --> 01:38:57.000
Not that I know of.

01:38:57.000 --> 01:39:05.000
You mentioned a few minutes ago a church in your home in Montgomery. Did she started? Can you tell us about that?

01:39:05.000 --> 01:39:12.000
Well, I moved to Montgomery. We just wanted to go to church.

01:39:12.000 --> 01:39:25.000
When the other grew up in the Congregational Church, it eventually became a United Church Christ when the Congregational moved merged with Evangelical and Reform Churches.

01:39:25.000 --> 01:39:32.000
And he said, well, there isn't a Congregational Church here in Montgomery. Let's start one.

01:39:32.000 --> 01:39:44.000
So we started in our home. And, you know, we built it up to about 20 people. And then we found we actually started meeting in the chapel of Huntingdon College.

01:39:44.000 --> 01:39:59.000
They let us use that on Sunday mornings for a while. And then we built a little building on the outskirts of Montgomery for a church out there.

01:39:59.000 --> 01:40:04.000
Did you just lay ministers in? Did you have a minister?

01:40:04.000 --> 01:40:19.000
No, we were like, oh, well, we eventually hired one. But Allen Henry was one of our visiting ministers until we hired a full-time minister.

01:40:19.000 --> 01:40:23.000
Looks like one of those Georgian nats is about to get it.

01:40:23.000 --> 01:40:28.000
I'm sorry, but it's not her.

01:40:28.000 --> 01:40:41.000
Anyway, there's a book that Millard (Dean) Fuller wrote. Actually, he was a pretty good writing diaries when he was in business.

01:40:41.000 --> 01:40:51.000
He kept a record of what was happening every day. And he would record other things that he was involved in, like developing the church.

01:40:51.000 --> 01:41:04.000
He helped to get some property and things like that. And I guess we were the largest donors in the Congregation until we laughed.

01:41:04.000 --> 01:41:20.000
10%, no, not even 1%. But we say that after we left, the church died. So our church membership died and went to heaven.

01:41:20.000 --> 01:41:32.000
And we didn't join another church until we joined Maranatha Baptist Church. Jimmy Carter twisted her arm. He said, okay, I've joined habitat now. I want you to join our church.

01:41:32.000 --> 01:41:42.000
So we did. Well, let's see now. Where, where, where, I think I got a little off track.

01:41:42.000 --> 01:41:51.000
I was actually in your in your biography and some of these high points that you put together, which is very helpful.

01:41:51.000 --> 01:42:10.000
I mentioned some of the law cases that your husband Millard (Dean) Fuller was involved with. You said, you said, you sort of representing some African Americans who were seeking employment and law enforcement.

01:42:10.000 --> 01:42:19.000
And then you mentioned here something about the Black boycott in Americus in 1971 and Maranatha.

01:42:19.000 --> 01:42:22.000
Tell us about some of that.

01:42:22.000 --> 01:42:36.000
Yeah, when we were living at Koinonia, we became aware of some pretty serious police brutality against black people.

01:42:36.000 --> 01:42:48.000
And at that time, the police force and the sheriff's county law enforcement also was totally white.

01:42:48.000 --> 01:43:02.000
And well, the schools were, you know, soon to integrate. But anyway, it was a real kind of volatile time when changes were taking place.

01:43:02.000 --> 01:43:14.000
But the law enforcement was totally white. And there, there were some Black people that wanted to get employed.

01:43:14.000 --> 01:43:31.000
Or, and things just kind of came to a head when there was so much brutality against black people. Very unfair administration of forcing laws.

01:43:31.000 --> 01:43:47.000
And so black people just were bailed. They kind of stood up and said, this has got to stop. And when it didn't, then they said, okay, well, we're not going to do any business in town.

01:43:47.000 --> 01:43:55.000
If we have to, we'll go to neighboring communities to buy groceries. And so that got the attention.

01:43:55.000 --> 01:44:07.000
That got the attention. There was, there was a march downtown Americus. and we actually participated in that as well as Millard (Dean) Fuller.

01:44:07.000 --> 01:44:19.000
And we walked down the streets. There was not a car. Everybody stayed in the stores. People were peering out the windows. I mean, everybody was afraid.

01:44:19.000 --> 01:44:35.000
You know, the riots were going to break out. But we wanted it to be a peaceful march. We just wanted to show some determination and demonstrate how serious, you know,

01:44:35.000 --> 01:44:52.000
that the situation was. So I can remember so well, there was a meeting called in one of the churches, Black churches. And Millard (Dean) Fuller was asked to speak. And, and everybody was just so riled up.

01:44:52.000 --> 01:45:07.000
And Millard (Dean) Fuller started speaking in his usual, you know, enthusiastic kind of tone. And he realized that he had to calm himself down because the crowd was about to lose it.

01:45:07.000 --> 01:45:28.000
And he was able to calm things down and to have a focus on what would actually bring about change. And he said, Some of you Black folks ought to step up.

01:45:28.000 --> 01:45:49.000
And so when they did, of course, they were turned down. But then they were able to file a law case. And so they eventually, some of them got hired. And then, and then there was a woman that wanted to get on the force here again, you know.

01:45:49.000 --> 01:46:09.000
And they used to excuse, oh, she's too pretty. You know, this might distract the men from doing their job. And Millard (Dean) Fuller said that won't watch. That will not watch. And so she got her hired.

01:46:09.000 --> 01:46:37.000
But then also he became aware of tremendous injustices as far as court cases, death, murder cases, or Black accused of murder. And he began to get involved in taking some of those, what we call death penalty or death row cases.

01:46:39.000 --> 01:47:00.000
And even if it was obvious that someone was guilty, it was really bad if they had killed a white person. That was almost certain death penalty. And all the juries were pretty much white.

01:47:00.000 --> 01:47:21.000
And Millard (Dean) Fuller just, Millard (Dean) Fuller figured out why or else in his, his partnering with people like Millard (Dean) Fuller Farmer in Atlanta, who was also doing a lot of death penalty cases.

01:47:21.000 --> 01:47:33.000
They discovered that Black folks did not believe in the death penalty because they were serious. They knew that it worked against Black people.

01:47:33.000 --> 01:47:49.000
So when there was a selection of the jury, all of an attorney had to do was to ask, do you believe in the death penalty? And they would say no. And they would never get selected.

01:47:49.000 --> 01:48:01.000
So therefore you had an all white jury. And it was easy to persuade them to come back with the verdict of guilty.

01:48:01.000 --> 01:48:21.000
They wanted to call for the death penalty. So Millard (Dean) Fuller was very persuasive. He was just great in the courtroom. And he took great pride in getting a jury to pray with him one time.

01:48:21.000 --> 01:48:33.000
He wanted to focus on this. This is really what God would want.

01:48:33.000 --> 01:48:43.000
And this was before the days when the courthouses were air conditioned. And about after lunch, things were good.

01:48:43.000 --> 01:48:57.000
It was hard for the jury, the person's on the jury to stay awake. And he would wait for one of them to nod off, you know, like this.

01:48:57.000 --> 01:49:15.000
And he said, he had started saying, this is a serious matter. Somebody's life, you know. And if you're a Christian, you need to really consider whether you should send this person to death.

01:49:15.000 --> 01:49:25.000
And he said, it's so serious. We need to pray about this. He said, let's bow our heads and look over the one that will sound asleep and say, thank you.

01:49:25.000 --> 01:49:31.000
And then people would think that he was already praying. And so they bow their heads.

01:49:31.000 --> 01:49:49.000
I'm saying whatever it took, he was able to bring justice a lot of times. It would involve, you know, life sentence, but at least kept people off of death row.

01:49:49.000 --> 01:50:01.000
Did you ever work with Donald Hollowell? Well, then in those cases, you know, Donald Hollowell, he was a black lawyer in Atlanta. He ended up working for the EEOC, I think at a certain point.

01:50:01.000 --> 01:50:10.000
But I think he was involved. It might have been a different era. But I think he was involved in trying to fight some of the inequities in the death-penalty cases in Georgia too.

01:50:10.000 --> 01:50:26.000
That name does not sound familiar. Millard practiced law until Habitat got so big that he just didn't, he just didn't have the time for it anymore.

01:50:26.000 --> 01:50:41.000
I thought it was a shame because he was so good. At one point, he partnered with an lawyer in Columbus who did the most of the preparation and the deputations on a case.

01:50:41.000 --> 01:50:53.000
And then a couple of days before, he would inform Millard of the facts and everything. And then Millard actually was lead lawyer in the case.

01:50:53.000 --> 01:51:01.000
But he had to give it up because Habitat was just growing at such a phenomenal rate.

01:51:01.000 --> 01:51:18.000
It was interesting for me to read more of the history because I guess I grew up with the idea of Habitat as this well established organization to learn more about how it was founded.

01:51:18.000 --> 01:51:26.000
It's really interesting to think of it as always as well established and successful.

01:51:26.000 --> 01:51:40.000
I was thinking about it a little bit. What was it like to participate in that March? Were you the only whites or only only whites in that March? You were mentioning it in Americus?

01:51:40.000 --> 01:51:50.000
We weren't the only whites. I think there were some other people from Koinonia Farm that participated in the Premier League.

01:51:50.000 --> 01:52:00.000
Yeah. What was it like to have any fear or any concerns about being part of the March?

01:52:00.000 --> 01:52:17.000
Yeah, a little bit. But you know, I knew what I was doing was right. And by that time we had lived at Koinonia Farm for a good long while.

01:52:17.000 --> 01:52:33.000
I had moved there in 68 and the March was 71. It was just that we were taught. You do what you fill in your heart is right.

01:52:33.000 --> 01:52:47.000
And if you get hot or get put in jail or even lose your life, you know, you've done the right thing. Take a stand for something.

01:52:47.000 --> 01:52:58.000
How do you think the civil rights movement and your... I mean it's obvious that your Christian faith is clearly so significant.

01:52:58.000 --> 01:53:06.000
Does that intersect with the civil rights movement and the ways that you view and miller of children's to focus your lives?

01:53:06.000 --> 01:53:24.000
Oh, absolutely. You know, it was part of what was the most prevalent at that time in history. It was the most obvious thing that needed to be changed.

01:53:24.000 --> 01:53:28.000
But the things that you missed about your old life?

01:53:28.000 --> 01:53:31.000
No.

01:53:31.000 --> 01:53:34.000
Not really.

01:53:34.000 --> 01:53:42.000
Yeah. Could you lose friends or any part of this white society?

01:53:42.000 --> 01:53:56.000
I'd say I gained a whole lot more friends than I lost. Oh yeah. That's understatement there.

01:53:56.000 --> 01:54:16.000
It was our families that were disgusted, really, disappointed. We were shunned by most of our family members on my side of the family and miller's side of the family.

01:54:16.000 --> 01:54:28.000
They just didn't get it. They didn't understand why we were running counter to the culture.

01:54:28.000 --> 01:54:36.000
In fact, there were a few. When we left business, gave our money away, they said, you need to be in a mental institution.

01:54:36.000 --> 01:54:48.000
They didn't get enough of all that money. But it was like what was holding us back from a real life and it destroyed our marriage. We just wanted to be done with it.

01:54:48.000 --> 01:54:51.000
You know, start totally over.

01:54:51.000 --> 01:54:56.000
Is it hard to deal with your family? Feelings?

01:54:56.000 --> 01:55:04.000
Yeah. Yeah, it was.

01:55:04.000 --> 01:55:17.000
My mother didn't want to discuss anything that was controversial. And we tried to have discussions with my dad. And we just finally gave up.

01:55:17.000 --> 01:55:23.000
We just kept it on a family and grandkids.

01:55:23.000 --> 01:55:36.000
What about your sister? My sister was very supportive. When she and her husband married a couple of years before we did, miller and I, they had moved to California.

01:55:36.000 --> 01:55:44.000
That was one of the heart of the liberal thinking out there.

01:55:44.000 --> 01:55:56.000
I should have made a mention of that. My sister certainly was an exception.

01:55:56.000 --> 01:56:06.000
It seems interesting that then Morris Dees also sort of seems to follow a similar path, I guess, without going to lot of family and Southern poverty law center.

01:56:06.000 --> 01:56:09.000
Exactly. Yeah.

01:56:09.000 --> 01:56:23.000
He started off, I think one of his first things was to integrate the Alabama state patrol.

01:56:23.000 --> 01:56:26.000
That's a challenge, yeah.

01:56:26.000 --> 01:56:37.000
That was a big deal. And then he got it more into representing people who had been harmed by the Klan or other subversive.

01:56:37.000 --> 01:56:55.000
Groups. His support has greatly expanded and diversified, you know, to other minority groups.

01:56:55.000 --> 01:57:00.000
Does that go back to that same incident with the Freedom Rides?

01:57:00.000 --> 01:57:05.000
I never asked him that question, but I would certainly think so.

01:57:05.000 --> 01:57:13.000
Did he stay in touch with you all and sort of do you think he was influenced by the decisions that you all made?

01:57:13.000 --> 01:57:18.000
I don't know. We didn't have much contact.

01:57:18.000 --> 01:57:30.000
We were really busy in to cornered in, Africa and work with Habitat.

01:57:30.000 --> 01:57:43.000
He was kind of doing his thing, you know, once and while our paths would cross, but there wasn't a whole lot of contact there.

01:57:43.000 --> 01:57:50.000
It was interesting, the trajectory.

01:57:50.000 --> 01:57:56.000
I haven't asked you a lot of questions about Habitat because I think it's more documented.

01:57:56.000 --> 01:58:08.000
But are there things that we haven't talked about that you think are particularly significant or that you focus on with Habitat or anything else?

01:58:08.000 --> 01:58:18.000
Well, I don't think so.

01:58:18.000 --> 01:58:29.000
If I had some time to reflect more on that and a later time, I might, but nothing comes to mind right now.

01:58:29.000 --> 01:58:55.000
More of those that's intrigued me, you're listening to you as converging of God's plan and practical things like houses and education.

01:58:55.000 --> 01:59:00.000
And the Civil Rights Movement, which was a moral and legal issue.

01:59:00.000 --> 01:59:09.000
Do you feel that it all fit together in some way? How does it all fit together?

01:59:09.000 --> 01:59:20.000
Well, it is. It is. It kind of all fits together. Everybody had their own piece of the puzzle, you know, putting it in at different times.

01:59:20.000 --> 01:59:34.000
It finally began to make sense and began to really make changes within the society, but it was very, very slow.

01:59:34.000 --> 01:59:39.000
Like, you know, any kind of major change in society takes a long, long time.

01:59:39.000 --> 02:00:00.000
But the thing that has been very interesting is the Civil Rights Movement has spurred so many other freedom movements outside the country with women, you know, with other minorities, even with the mentally ill.

02:00:00.000 --> 02:00:23.000
The Civil Rights Movement proved that people could speak out and demonstrate another way and eventually get to people's hearts and minds and make real change happen.

02:00:23.000 --> 02:00:41.000
But sometimes, you know, it takes years to put all those pieces together. And I think that to put it in religious terms, we're all called to different pieces of that puzzle.

02:00:41.000 --> 02:00:52.000
And it was always interesting to me to see how people kind of grouped together. We'll work on this, you know, we'll work on that, we'll do this, we'll do that, you know.

02:00:52.000 --> 02:01:09.000
And just how it all evolved. And those patterns that were set on how the Civil Rights Movement unfolded is a great pattern,

02:01:09.000 --> 02:01:30.000
a great demonstration, a great template on what kind of work it takes to make other changes, whether it's getting people to wear their seat belts, or, you know, provide health care.

02:01:30.000 --> 02:01:48.000
You know, there's a lot of changes that are going on right now in our society. It just takes time, takes people courageously speaking out, making sacrifices.

02:01:48.000 --> 02:01:57.000
So are those some of the things that you think were most significant about the Civil Rights Movement at being willing to take a stand and speak out?

02:01:57.000 --> 02:02:11.000
Oh, absolutely. People putting their lives on the line. I heard Andrew Young speak once, telling some of the stories.

02:02:11.000 --> 02:02:29.000
I can remember one in particular about the Birmingham Children's Crusade May 1963, and deciding, everybody just deciding to sit down, you know.

02:02:29.000 --> 02:02:49.000
And I hadn't planned to do that. It just, someone started sitting down as a gesture of being humble, and they eventually turned those hoses off.

02:02:49.000 --> 02:03:06.000
And there's just some powerful stories. I can't wait to see some of the other interviews. And now you've already watched a couple that already been posted on the website.

02:03:06.000 --> 02:03:14.000
So I think it's going to be a remarkable addition to our history. So I'm really glad that you were able to talk to us.

02:03:14.000 --> 02:03:30.000
Well, at the beginning, I was more of an observer, kind of taking it all in, being educated by my husband's experiences, of opening up to a wider variety of people.

02:03:30.000 --> 02:03:51.000
And then my contacts with people all over the United States and all over the world, and seeing that everybody has certain things in common, no matter where they are, or what color scan, or whatever culture they come in.

02:03:51.000 --> 02:04:10.000
I would relate to people, even if I couldn't speak the language. You know, I would make gestures towards their children, you know, and I could tell them a little bit about my children, you know, and people have grandchildren.

02:04:10.000 --> 02:04:29.000
I've heard similar things from the Carter, Jimmy and Rosalyn Carter, how they would relate to big, important statesmen, statesmen around the world, just get down on a real common human level.

02:04:29.000 --> 02:04:42.000
And people really appreciated. I mean, Millard was so good at this one, we would visit, he would make a fool out of himself dancing in Africa.

02:04:42.000 --> 02:04:52.000
And then, you know, how it was make the crowds go berserk, you know, because they'd never seen a white man making a fool of themselves before.

02:04:52.000 --> 02:05:01.000
They were accustomed, you know, these diff-stri-type suit dignitaries, you know, that kind of ordered them around.

02:05:01.000 --> 02:05:12.000
I always enjoyed getting down on a real human level with people and making them know that we care about them.

02:05:12.000 --> 02:05:30.000
And I think that's what's going to change the world, make it a better place for everybody. We enjoyed it. I mean, that became our life is meeting people and helping to make a difference.

02:05:30.000 --> 02:05:35.000
How does it influence your children?

02:05:35.000 --> 02:05:59.000
Oh, I think it's greatly impacted them. The experience of us living at Koinonia Farm, seeing a different way of life, very meaningful, deeply religiously rooted way of life, meeting people who were some were very different.

02:05:59.000 --> 02:06:12.000
Some were really weird, actually. But being able to accept everybody, no matter how different, or where they came from.

02:06:12.000 --> 02:06:28.000
And then the experience overseas, the three years in Africa, why our son and seminary applied for a job to work in Saudi Arabia, that Saudi Saudi Saudi Saudi Aramco.

02:06:28.000 --> 02:06:38.000
He was leading the kids of Americans and Europeans in their summer activities when they were out of school.

02:06:38.000 --> 02:06:47.000
And he got that job basically because he had had international living experience. There were three others that applied, but he got the job because he had that.

02:06:47.000 --> 02:07:05.000
They never, they never meet a stranger. Some of our kids have been more engaged in worthwhile church and community activities.

02:07:05.000 --> 02:07:21.000
They're all four of them are, you know, their own person. And we never have tried to force them. They've been on bills with us. They've started student habitat groups, habitat, habitat campus chapters, they're called.

02:07:21.000 --> 02:07:31.000
They've been involved, been involved with the effort that we started in 2005 after we left habitat, the Fuller Center for Housing.

02:07:31.000 --> 02:07:43.000
That's a shirt Fuller Center for Housing. And, you know, we have a daughter-in-law who is actually on staff, helps raise money for the Fuller Center.

02:07:43.000 --> 02:07:59.000
They've started a group in their communities. Our daughter, out in Texas, who is a home builder for very upscale housing.

02:07:59.000 --> 02:08:13.000
Not like the ones that we built with habitat in the Fuller Center, but they got her to lead a habitat house in Benton, Texas.

02:08:13.000 --> 02:08:27.000
So, they've been involved in different ways, but, you know, they've had their education, their families, you know, their families raising their families.

02:08:27.000 --> 02:08:41.000
And, they haven't done it full time, but each has done something in their own way.

02:08:41.000 --> 02:08:45.000
You sure? Anything you'd like to add?

02:08:45.000 --> 02:08:53.000
I know, there's probably some stories.

02:08:53.000 --> 02:08:59.000
Oh, let me just think a minute.

02:08:59.000 --> 02:09:07.000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.
